i so the people
started to sing i

14:51.440 --> 14:53.226
the thing that was amazing to me

14:53.526 --> 14:55.357
was just the sheer...

14:55.653 --> 14:59.316
like, almost seemed like
an unlimited types of music.

14:59.615 --> 15:02.732
things like spoken word
and comedy and sound effects

15:03.035 --> 15:06.243
and international and jazz,
trend jazz, big band,

15:06.539 --> 15:07.824
i mean, it was unbelievable.

15:08.124 --> 15:09.580
Tower wasn't just a group
of departments,

15:09.875 --> 15:12.457
it was a group of little stores
within one roof,

15:12.753 --> 15:15.210
i mean, there was a jazz store,
there was a classical store,

15:15.506 --> 15:17.212
and you got to know
those people,

15:17.508 --> 15:19.464
they got to know your tastes,
you got to know theirs,

15:19.760 --> 15:21.375
that's how you learned
about music,

15:21.679 --> 15:24.512
and that's also what
brought you back into the store.

15:24.807 --> 15:26.923
[russ]all of a sudden,
it would become fashionable

15:27.226 --> 15:29.182
for those young people
to find something

15:29.478 --> 15:31.218
that they want
to hold in their hand,

15:31.522 --> 15:35.014
that they want to collect,
that it's hip to collect,

15:35.317 --> 15:36.477
that has music on it.

15:36.777 --> 15:39.063
well, first,
there was the thrill

15:39.363 --> 15:42.571
of being surrounded by music.

15:42.867 --> 15:45.700
80 percent of it
is a complete mystery to you.

15:45.995 --> 15:48.532
so when we came west,
we were shocked

15:48.831 --> 15:51.948
at the size of Tower Records,
and simply,

15:52.251 --> 15:55.835
how many records there were.
[chuckles]

15:56.130 --> 15:59.873
everybody in a record store
is a little bit of your friend

16:00.176 --> 16:03.213
for twenty minutes or so,
you know? [chuckles]

16:03.512 --> 16:07.676
so there was that family aspect
of a real record store.

16:07.975 --> 16:09.840
it started out as a small family

16:10.144 --> 16:12.135
here in sacramento
with just a few of us

16:12.438 --> 16:15.225
and as time went on,
the company got bigger
and bigger and bigger,

16:15.524 --> 16:17.515
it just became a bigger
and bigger family.

16:17.818 --> 16:19.558
[heidi]it was
my second year in college

16:19.862 --> 16:21.773
and I didn't like college.
i was moving out of the house

16:22.072 --> 16:23.482
and I decided
i needed to get a job.

16:23.783 --> 16:25.398
i wanted to go some place
and make some money.

16:25.701 --> 16:27.737
i applied for the record store
on watt avenue.

16:28.037 --> 16:29.573
they weren't hiring girls
that year,

16:29.872 --> 16:31.737
they'd already had one
and she hadn't worked out.

16:32.041 --> 16:33.952
so th ese two gentlemen that
were running the bookstore,

16:34.251 --> 16:35.866
and the bookstore opened
in '62,

16:36.170 --> 16:38.001
so it had only
been open for three years.

16:38.297 --> 16:41.130
they wouldn't let us
wear pants, either.
we had to wear skirts.

16:41.425 --> 16:43.040
so they could, of course,
look up our skirts.

16:43.344 --> 16:44.800
[russ]heidi was a girl
that worked for me

16:45.095 --> 16:47.131
in the book division,
in the bookstore,

16:47.431 --> 16:49.672
the very first bookstore
in sacramento.

16:49.975 --> 16:52.387
[heidi]he walks into the store
and the first thing he sees
in this bookstore

16:52.686 --> 16:54.426
is this woman
in leopard skin underwear

16:54.730 --> 16:57.016
and a mini skirt
hanging desiderata posters,

16:57.316 --> 16:58.806
and that was me.

16:59.109 --> 17:02.567
i showed up, and I wasn't
a weenie, and I worked hard,

17:02.863 --> 17:05.194
and I wasn't going
to be put down.

17:05.491 --> 17:08.324
and learned how to swear,
and learned how to drink,

17:08.618 --> 17:10.483
i learned how to do drugs.
[laughs]

17:10.788 --> 17:13.154
[mark viducich]
i think we were with
some friends one afternoon,

17:13.457 --> 17:15.038
it was late evening,

17:15.334 --> 17:17.494
honest to god I think we stole
a couple of records from Tower,

17:17.795 --> 17:19.251
and it wasn't the
last one I ever took

17:19.547 --> 17:21.287
after I started working there,
of course,

17:21.589 --> 17:22.704
but it was fun.

17:23.008 --> 17:24.589
first day,
i think I went to el chico,

17:24.885 --> 17:26.590
which was the local bar
down the street,

17:26.887 --> 17:29.378
probably spent three hours
at lunch having a few cocktails

17:29.682 --> 17:31.047
and came back to work.

17:31.350 --> 17:33.386
that's pretty much how
it went for a long time.

17:33.686 --> 17:37.019
mark is crazy,
he's totally nuts.

17:37.314 --> 17:38.645
but he could do anything.

17:38.941 --> 17:40.477
viducich, sid vicious,
we called him sid vicious

17:40.776 --> 17:42.732
because he was the nastiest
mother on the planet.

17:43.028 --> 17:45.735
you know he could ream your ass
like nobody's business.

17:46.031 --> 17:47.521
i'll go drink
whenever the hell I want,

17:47.825 --> 17:49.315
and please don't ever
talk to me that way again.

17:49.618 --> 17:51.404
no, there was nothing like that.

17:51.704 --> 17:52.910
course it helped
that your best friend

17:53.205 --> 17:54.490
was the manager
of the store, too.

17:54.790 --> 17:57.247
my dad and russ
are first cousins.

17:57.543 --> 18:01.627
my father actually ran the cafe
at the Tower drugstore.

18:01.922 --> 18:04.254
and so that's where the
connection is with Tower drugs.

18:04.550 --> 18:08.168
so my father actually ended up
working at Tower Records too.

18:08.470 --> 18:11.337
he did store development
for russ for many years,

18:11.640 --> 18:14.757
so when we built new stores,
my father, ross,

18:15.060 --> 18:16.596
was the person who built
those stores,

18:16.896 --> 18:18.887
so obviously,
it was easy for me to get a job

18:19.189 --> 18:21.350
working at Tower
when I got out of high school.

18:21.650 --> 18:22.639
i went to work
for the book division

18:22.943 --> 18:26.026
as a clerk and then advertising.

18:26.322 --> 18:28.438
so I ran the advertising
for the book division.

18:28.741 --> 18:30.277
then I went into
community relations,

18:30.576 --> 18:32.737
and bringing in authors
for book signings.

18:33.037 --> 18:36.200
virtually everyone in the
company started off as a clerk.

18:36.498 --> 18:38.454
they'd become buyers,
they'd become

18:38.751 --> 18:41.288
supervisor types
in the store.

18:41.587 --> 18:44.294
th ey'd become assistant managers
and then they'd become managers,

18:44.590 --> 18:46.296
so they learn everything
they need to learn.

18:46.592 --> 18:49.925
and the entire development
of Tower Records

18:50.220 --> 18:53.508
through the entire period
of time it existed

18:53.807 --> 18:55.547
was just that kind of a thing.

18:55.851 --> 18:57.466
[heidi]as a woman,
i just said,

18:57.770 --> 18:59.055
"i'm not even going to think
about being a woman."

18:59.355 --> 19:01.095
there're no excuses,
no period stuff.

19:01.398 --> 19:03.980
I mean, I went in to labor
twice behind the counter.

19:04.276 --> 19:07.484
because I was determined
to be treated as an equal,

19:07.780 --> 19:09.520
because I was
the first female hired,

19:09.823 --> 19:11.484
I was the first
female vice president,

19:11.784 --> 19:12.864
I was the first female
general manager,

19:13.160 --> 19:14.366
I was the first manager,

19:14.662 --> 19:17.620
so I unknowingly
had this responsibility

19:17.915 --> 19:19.325
to be kind of the mentor

19:19.625 --> 19:21.616
for these women
coming up behind me.

19:21.919 --> 19:24.626
[russ]
it isn't what we as a company
could teach our employees,

19:24.922 --> 19:27.789
but what other employees
could teach each other.

19:28.092 --> 19:31.801
that family kind of thing
is what made the company grow,

19:32.096 --> 19:33.711
and what made
the company successful.

19:34.014 --> 19:35.550
i'm convinced of that.

19:35.849 --> 19:37.760
that's my old tom sawyer
theory of management.

19:38.060 --> 19:39.641
let somebody else
paint the fence.

19:39.937 --> 19:42.019
but we had the freedom to do
whatever we wanted,

19:42.314 --> 19:45.101
I mean he literally
gave us these stores
with all this product in it,

19:45.401 --> 19:49.735
and said, "okay, show up,
do the job right,

19:50.030 --> 19:52.521
don't screw me over."
and then left us alone.

19:52.825 --> 19:55.282
one key to the success
of Tower Records,

19:55.577 --> 19:57.192
particularly in that period,

19:57.496 --> 19:58.656
is we had no dress code.

19:58.956 --> 20:00.912
I really believe
that a lot of people

20:01.208 --> 20:04.200
wanted to come to work for us,
young people especially,

20:04.503 --> 20:07.165
so they wouldn't have
to be told how to dress.

20:07.464 --> 20:09.295
[Ken Sockolov] The people
who worked at Tower

20:09.591 --> 20:11.297
were musicians
in many cases.

20:11.593 --> 20:13.129
[Dave Grohl]
I got a job at Tower Records

20:13.429 --> 20:16.136
because that's the only place
I could get a job

20:16.432 --> 20:18.468
with my fucking haircut.

20:18.767 --> 20:20.883
that is the truth.
[chuckles]

20:21.186 --> 20:23.393
I love Tower Records,
and I love music,

20:23.689 --> 20:26.931
and I only wanted
to work at Tower Records

20:27.234 --> 20:30.897
and be surrounded
by these cool people
and all this cool music.

20:31.196 --> 20:32.936
I just imagined
that everybody that worked

20:33.240 --> 20:34.730
at Tower
was like an aficionado.

20:35.034 --> 20:37.241
they didn't necessarily have
any other kind of skills,

20:37.536 --> 20:42.030
sometimes even people skills,
but they had musical knowledge.

20:42.332 --> 20:44.869
every music store,
whether it was a place
to go buy drumsticks,

20:45.169 --> 20:46.579
or a place to go buy records,

20:46.879 --> 20:49.586
were total snobs, total snobs.

20:49.882 --> 20:51.088
the record store
especially was,

20:51.383 --> 20:53.544
had a reputation of
being incredibly rude.

20:53.844 --> 20:55.380
and fuck you if you
can't take a joke.

20:55.679 --> 20:58.921
so, heh, it was more of
a battlefield to get music,

20:59.224 --> 21:01.931
to get records out of
the store in the earlier days.

21:02.227 --> 21:04.013
[stan]
when we opened up at sunset,

21:04.313 --> 21:07.350
that, I feel,
really put us on the mar

21:10.235 --> 21:13.978
larry carp called russ,
"you gotta see this location.
the best thing in the world."

21:14.281 --> 21:15.942
and he goes down there,

21:16.241 --> 21:18.232
and it was
a mad man muntz location,

21:18.535 --> 21:21.993
where you could get
a four track player
installed in your car

21:22.289 --> 21:24.029
right at the corner
of sunset and horn.

21:24.333 --> 21:26.540
[russ]it was 4,000 bucks
a month for a land lease.

21:26.835 --> 21:28.450
that meant I had
to build a building.

21:28.754 --> 21:31.461
so my cousin ross
comes to the rescue again,

21:31.757 --> 21:34.715
and he says,
"all right, we'll just build
a building on there."

21:35.010 --> 21:36.341
I said, "okay, do it."

21:36.637 --> 21:39.003
[stan]it was
the first building we built.

21:39.306 --> 21:41.592
[russ]it was
a pre-fab building
that's still standing

21:41.892 --> 21:43.223
forty years later,
fifty years later,

21:43.519 --> 21:44.599
whatever it is.

21:44.895 --> 21:46.476
[stan]it was a concrete slab,

21:46.772 --> 21:49.855
and then these metal girders
that went up and over

21:50.150 --> 21:53.358
filled in with concrete
block and glass,

21:53.654 --> 21:56.236
and an orange tile floor.

21:56.532 --> 21:58.614
and some counters, that was it.
I laid the floor

21:58.909 --> 22:00.991
at Tower Sunset,
with these two hands.

22:01.286 --> 22:05.950
ross built that building,
the entire project for $75,000.

22:06.250 --> 22:07.740
nobody else would do that.

22:08.043 --> 22:09.624
you know, they have
the whole process

22:09.920 --> 22:11.035
of getting the store ready,

22:11.338 --> 22:12.794
then getting the racks
put together,

22:13.090 --> 22:15.672
and getting the merchandise
put in and so on.

22:15.968 --> 22:17.754
stan was there
from the beginning.

22:18.053 --> 22:20.669
I would come home
from working all day,

22:20.973 --> 22:22.964
which really was
digging ditches

22:23.267 --> 22:25.849
and laying floors,
and getting all sweaty,

22:26.145 --> 22:27.806
but the nice thing was,
record companies would come by

22:28.105 --> 22:29.811
and drop off promos
every once in a while,

22:30.107 --> 22:32.018
and when i'd get home,
i'd have some new records.

22:32.317 --> 22:35.980
well, I just saw
this guy schlepping albums up,

22:36.280 --> 22:37.770
a good twelve steps
to his level,

22:38.073 --> 22:40.314
and then it was
even farther to mine,

22:40.617 --> 22:43.575
but I just saw him,
and i'm a very friendly guy,

22:43.871 --> 22:46.032
and just went down and said,
"hi, i'm your neighbor."

22:46.331 --> 22:49.949
and bob would come down
from his apartment

22:50.252 --> 22:52.368
to check out, see if I had
any new promos.

22:52.671 --> 22:55.037
he was really nice,
he was very open to me,

22:55.340 --> 22:59.583
I didn't know him,
but we became very good friends.

22:59.887 --> 23:01.969
[stan]i'll never forget,
one day I came home

23:02.264 --> 23:04.050
and my front door was open,

23:04.349 --> 23:05.805
and I thought,
"well, that's odd."

23:06.101 --> 23:07.637
I walk in,
and I hear splashing.

23:07.936 --> 23:09.801
well yeah,
I mean it got hot in L.A.

23:10.105 --> 23:11.720
when stan went to work,

23:12.024 --> 23:13.639
bob'd go in to his apartment
and smoke dope

23:13.942 --> 23:15.728
and listen to stan's records.

23:16.028 --> 23:17.768
but yeah, he came home
and I was soaking

23:18.071 --> 23:20.653
in his tub,
listening to records.

23:20.949 --> 23:23.190
that did it,
I was really pissed.

23:23.493 --> 23:27.577
so I said, "well bob, no,
but it's time for you
to get a job.

23:27.873 --> 23:30.580
"we need a receiving clerk.
why don't you be a
receiving clerk. "

23:30.876 --> 23:32.912
in november, actually,
they opened the store.

23:33.212 --> 23:34.577
so I had hung around
for quite a bit,

23:34.880 --> 23:36.290
he said,
"come in the store and apply,"

23:36.590 --> 23:38.922
and I did, and charlie shaw,
the manager at the time,

23:39.218 --> 23:41.129
hired me, immediately.

23:41.428 --> 23:42.884
and then once I got
in the door,

23:43.180 --> 23:45.136
I just fell in love
with being in the building.

23:45.432 --> 23:47.764
I had no clue
about the record industry,

23:48.060 --> 23:50.176
but it was, to me,
right up my alley.

23:50.479 --> 23:52.720
this is like being home
with a bunch of friends,

23:53.023 --> 23:55.059
and much more fun
than i'd ever had

23:55.359 --> 23:57.065
in any of my previous jobs.

23:57.361 --> 23:58.817
[russ]again, now here,

23:59.112 --> 24:00.522
we hadn't opened a store
since san francisco,

24:00.822 --> 24:02.938
and the same thing happened
in los angeles.

24:03.242 --> 24:06.780
we were in the midst
of a marvelous audience,

24:07.079 --> 24:09.035
I mean you had
this variety of people

24:09.331 --> 24:12.789
with all kinds of musical
tastes and money. [chuckles]

24:13.085 --> 24:15.827
[Bob Delanoy] I mean,
I knew sunset was like the focus

24:16.129 --> 24:17.835
of the whole
record industry, there.

24:18.131 --> 24:19.712
if you didn't get it
in that store,

24:20.008 --> 24:21.873
their whole rest
of their marketing crew

24:22.177 --> 24:24.133
thought you were doing
a shit job.

24:24.429 --> 24:25.794
[russ]
but imagine where we were.

24:26.098 --> 24:28.134
we were within
walking distance, virtually,

24:28.433 --> 24:31.391
of the entire record industry,
in the l.a. area.

24:31.687 --> 24:33.518
[Steve Nikkel] I think that was
a good strategy, I mean,

24:33.814 --> 24:36.226
if you're about music, you go
to where the music's being made.

24:36.525 --> 24:38.686
in los angeles,
especially in san francisco,

24:38.986 --> 24:41.944
so many of the artists
lived in our neighborhood.

24:42.239 --> 24:45.356
I mean, we were the local record
store for them, so it was great.

24:45.659 --> 24:48.366
[Stan] I remember David Geffen
coming in to the store
one saturday,

24:48.662 --> 24:50.698
and I was chatting with him,
and he says,

24:50.998 --> 24:52.829
"hey, you gotta come listen
to this record.ii

24:53.125 --> 24:55.241
I go, "okay."
so I hop into his car

24:55.544 --> 24:57.455
and we drive up into
the hollywood hills somewhere

24:57.754 --> 24:58.834
to where he was living,

24:59.131 --> 25:01.668
and he took out
an acetate test pressing,

25:01.967 --> 25:03.457
he put it on, and he played it,

25:03.760 --> 25:05.296
and it was the eagles'
first record.

25:05.595 --> 25:06.926
[david]you had the troubadour,
and you had the roxy,

25:07.222 --> 25:08.462
and you had the whiskey,

25:08.765 --> 25:11.222
and lots of clubs
that they played coming up,

25:11.518 --> 25:13.054
so those artists
would look through Tower

25:13.353 --> 25:14.889
wonder when their records
were going to be there,

25:15.188 --> 25:16.928
and would they have piles,
that kind of thing.

25:17.232 --> 25:19.598
if you loved music,
and having a record collection,

25:19.901 --> 25:22.392
which, I did,
it was exciting
to walk through the store.

25:22.696 --> 25:25.153
I went there
three or four times a week.

25:25.449 --> 25:27.815
we just drove down
sunset boulevard...

25:28.118 --> 25:31.861
[chuckles]
and we were just eyeballing
everything we could see,

25:32.164 --> 25:34.906
and there was
a huge record store.

25:35.208 --> 25:38.746
it was that place
where your dreams

25:39.046 --> 25:41.037
meet the listener.

25:41.340 --> 25:44.628
that's where
the final connection was made.

25:44.926 --> 25:46.382
that audience you dreamt of

25:46.678 --> 25:49.636
is walking
through the door right now.

25:49.931 --> 25:52.923
and you can stand there
and watch that happen.

25:53.226 --> 25:54.841
they are your listeners.

25:55.145 --> 25:56.931
and the place also served

25:57.230 --> 25:59.346
as kind of a lost boys club,

25:59.649 --> 26:02.356
so if you were
a young musician,

26:02.652 --> 26:05.940
you came into town
and you didn't know what to do,

26:06.239 --> 26:08.901
the first thing you did
is you went to Tower Records.

26:09.201 --> 26:11.317
artists who were in california
and in los angeles

26:11.620 --> 26:14.157
would go into
Tower Records to find out
where their records were.

26:14.456 --> 26:15.741
and if there was
a pile of elton john

26:16.041 --> 26:17.872
and there wasn't
a pile of the eagles,

26:18.168 --> 26:19.874
the eagles weren't happy,
or vice versa.

26:20.170 --> 26:22.126
I mean there were
a couple people that came in

26:22.422 --> 26:24.128
to the store
that I was so in awe of,

26:24.424 --> 26:27.382
I couldn't even, you know,
I couldn't even approach them.

26:27.677 --> 26:29.508
eric clapton, when he came in,

26:29.805 --> 26:33.172
jimmy page, pete townshend,
it was a constant flow.

26:33.475 --> 26:35.056
and nobody ever bothered them.

26:35.352 --> 26:37.809
I mean, they had a place there
where they could go

26:38.105 --> 26:39.845
and maybe a few people,
"oh, look over there.

26:40.148 --> 26:41.684
there's elton john,"
or whatever,

26:41.983 --> 26:43.189
but they kind of knew,

26:43.485 --> 26:44.975
that was a place
where you could hang

26:45.278 --> 26:47.109
and not really worry
about anybody hassling you.

26:47.406 --> 26:49.271
tuesday mornings
I would be at Tower Records

26:49.574 --> 26:52.316
at 10:00, 9:00 in la.

26:52.619 --> 26:54.234
the store'd open at nine
and they'd let me in.

26:54.538 --> 26:56.904
and it was a ritual,
and it was a ritual I loved.

26:57.207 --> 26:58.492
it was, you know,
my music center.

26:58.792 --> 27:01.033
yeah, I knew
where everything was.

27:01.336 --> 27:03.167
and if they didn't have
something in one week,

27:03.463 --> 27:04.703
or the next week,

27:05.006 --> 27:07.338
I told them, I said,
"you need to get this in."

27:07.634 --> 27:10.376
well elton was one
that used to come
even during business hours.

27:10.679 --> 27:12.169
he'd come in
with his limo driver.

27:12.472 --> 27:14.008
