we'd take our classical buyer,
and our assistant manager,

39:18.447 --> 39:21.063
and our favorite rock buyer,
and a couple managers,

39:21.367 --> 39:24.109
and go camp out for
a couple of weeks in a store.

39:24.412 --> 39:25.948
bringing the racks in,
marking the records,

39:26.247 --> 39:27.578
putting the records
in the shelves,

39:27.874 --> 39:29.535
setting everything up
so it really helped

39:29.834 --> 39:31.540
make you feel like
you were part of a team,

39:31.836 --> 39:34.327
but it also made you feel like
you were personally successful

39:34.630 --> 39:37.292
because you were able
to be part of this.

39:37.592 --> 39:38.672
[russ]so by 1979,

39:38.968 --> 39:41.459
we were really
a west coast operation.

39:41.762 --> 39:43.673
we'd opened stores
all the way from seattle

39:43.973 --> 39:45.338
to san diego,

39:45.641 --> 39:47.757
and then we went over
to phoenix and tempe.

39:48.060 --> 39:50.642
so a couple of guys came over
and visited me,

39:50.938 --> 39:53.270
hugh sazaki and akehana zowa.

39:53.566 --> 39:57.058
they said they wanted to start
up Tower Records in japan.

39:57.361 --> 39:59.147
these two gentlemen,
aki and hugh,

39:59.447 --> 40:01.062
had come to sacramento,
met with russ,

40:01.365 --> 40:03.071
and russ would fall
for any idea,

40:03.367 --> 40:04.948
and then they went back
to japan,

40:05.244 --> 40:07.951
and then a few weeks later
called up and said,

40:08.247 --> 40:09.783
"come on over.
we want to show you around."

40:10.082 --> 40:11.572
so they sent us
a couple of tickets.

40:11.876 --> 40:14.709
we traveled all over japan,
saw the sights,

40:15.004 --> 40:17.461
saw the existing
record retailers over there.

40:17.757 --> 40:19.418
[mark]
but one guy up in sapporo,

40:19.717 --> 40:22.174
which was a little island on
the northern border of japan,

40:22.470 --> 40:24.335
i think had stolen the name
Tower Records,

40:24.639 --> 40:26.630
and literally
had a Tower Record store.

40:26.933 --> 40:28.423
we said, "oh, no."

40:28.726 --> 40:30.717
so we went up
and we saw this, and said,

40:31.020 --> 40:32.385
"that's not very nice,
you've stolen our name.

40:32.688 --> 40:34.269
you shouldn't have done that. "

40:34.565 --> 40:36.897
but at least, if we open
our wholesale operation here,

40:37.193 --> 40:39.980
will you let us sell you
the imported records,

40:40.279 --> 40:41.735
and you guys run it?

40:42.031 --> 40:43.316
so that's how it started.

40:45.618 --> 40:48.701
russ was always enthusiastic
about something new.

40:48.996 --> 40:51.032
everybody else
on the record side hated it.

40:51.332 --> 40:52.913
they said, "we're an american
record company,

40:53.209 --> 40:54.699
we sell retail in america."

40:55.002 --> 40:56.492
they didn't know anything
about japan.

40:56.796 --> 40:58.878
russ didn't have any kind
of attitude like that.

40:59.173 --> 41:01.289
and they had no desire
to do it.

41:01.592 --> 41:03.674
they didn't care, it was just
one of russ' little projects.

41:03.970 --> 41:05.710
i was just a nobody receiving
clerk, and I said,

41:06.013 --> 41:07.844
"hell, i'll help you out.
whatever you want to do."

41:08.140 --> 41:09.880
our job at Tower Broadway

41:10.184 --> 41:12.470
was we would pull the records
out of stock from broadway,

41:12.770 --> 41:14.510
and ship them to japan,

41:14.814 --> 41:16.224
and that's when
i first got involved with russ,

41:16.524 --> 41:17.809
as I was the shipping
and receiving clerk

41:18.109 --> 41:20.225
making probably
five bucks an hour.

41:20.528 --> 41:22.143
that's how russ
and I became friends.

41:22.446 --> 41:24.903
nobody else would help him.

41:25.199 --> 41:26.780
[russ]
this goes on for a few months,

41:27.076 --> 41:29.658
and things are not really
looking all that good.

41:29.954 --> 41:31.569
we don't know
what is going wrong,

41:31.872 --> 41:34.579
but sad but true, they didn't
know what they were doing,

41:34.875 --> 41:36.160
and they weren't
very good at it.

41:36.460 --> 41:38.121
[mark] I think it was
a friday evening,

41:38.421 --> 41:40.036
and probably russ and i,
i know I was in russ' office,

41:40.339 --> 41:41.624
and we had been drinking,

41:41.924 --> 41:43.130
had a few cocktails,
you know, as you would

41:43.426 --> 41:44.882
wind down after a tough day.

41:45.177 --> 41:46.667
somehow the subject came up,

41:46.971 --> 41:48.836
"who am I going to send
to japan?"

41:49.140 --> 41:51.347
and he asked me that question,
"who am I going
to send to japan?"

41:51.642 --> 41:53.428
and I said,
"the only guy to send is me."

41:53.728 --> 41:55.969
and he goes,
"what do you mean, you?
you're not a store manager,

41:56.272 --> 41:57.603
you don't know
anything about it. "

41:57.898 --> 41:59.308
and I said,
"well, i'm the one

41:59.608 --> 42:00.768
who's been doing
all this work for japan."

42:01.068 --> 42:02.399
he goes, "do you think
you can do it?"

42:02.695 --> 42:04.811
i said, "sure."
he goes, "then go."

42:05.114 --> 42:06.229
you didn't have to go through
a bunch of people

42:06.532 --> 42:07.817
to make a decision
at Tower Records.

42:08.117 --> 42:09.072
he was the worst person to send

42:09.368 --> 42:10.528
i would ever think
in my life.

42:10.828 --> 42:11.908
i mean he had
the social skills

42:12.204 --> 42:13.239
of a warthog in heat,
you kidding me?

42:13.539 --> 42:15.154
but I think the reason
that they did,

42:15.458 --> 42:17.244
is he knew a lot
about shipping and receiving,

42:17.543 --> 42:19.829
he'd learned about
international shipping.

42:20.129 --> 42:22.040
they needed somebody to know
about how to get the product
in and out of there.

42:22.340 --> 42:24.080
i'd only been there
two and a half years.

42:24.383 --> 42:26.749
i saw it as an opportunity
to do something.

42:28.596 --> 42:30.382
[russ]we had no idea
what we're doing.

42:30.681 --> 42:33.673
i'll be honest with you,
we had not a clue.

42:33.976 --> 42:35.182
but we did it anyhow.

42:35.478 --> 42:36.968
i had literally
no idea what to expect.

42:37.271 --> 42:39.262
i'd never been to japan,
i had to go get a passport.

42:39.565 --> 42:41.772
we had a warehouse in akasaka,

42:42.068 --> 42:44.650
which is like the beverly hills
of tokyo, for god's sakes.

42:44.945 --> 42:46.276
we had this little warehouse,

42:46.572 --> 42:47.857
and I was supposed
to be there for six months.

42:48.157 --> 42:49.272
that was my deal,
you got six months

42:49.575 --> 42:51.782
to go either fix it or close it.

42:54.038 --> 42:55.778
[mark]shibuya was a little
like times square,

42:56.082 --> 42:57.822
laginsu was a little
like times square.

42:58.125 --> 42:59.865
tokyo was like times square.

43:00.169 --> 43:01.284
i mean the place
was always lit ur

43:01.587 --> 43:03.919
at nighttime, tokyo came alive.

43:06.008 --> 43:09.216
shibuya was a very hip,
more of a younger area

43:09.512 --> 43:11.594
for stores and kids
and people to hang out.

43:11.889 --> 43:13.971
the japan ese at that time
were very much

43:14.266 --> 43:16.052
into the culture
of american music.

43:16.352 --> 43:18.138
so I called russ, and said,
"russ, we're not closing

43:18.437 --> 43:19.973
the wholesale operation,

43:20.272 --> 43:21.387
we're going to
open up a retail store."

43:21.690 --> 43:23.681
and that set off
quite a firestorm

43:23.984 --> 43:26.441
of controversy to say the least.

43:26.737 --> 43:29.194
[mark]the push back
from stateside was,

43:29.490 --> 43:30.946
"you guys are crazy,
you're not going to do it."

43:31.242 --> 43:33.107
that was probably
bud's first impression.

43:33.411 --> 43:34.776
[mike]
bud wanted to be profitable.

43:35.079 --> 43:37.661
he didn't care so much
about being big.

43:37.957 --> 43:42.166
if you don't take advantage
of a new idea,

43:42.461 --> 43:45.294
if it makes any sense at all,

43:45.589 --> 43:46.999
then you've lost something.

43:48.926 --> 43:50.712
[mark]
russ wasn't omnipotent

43:51.011 --> 43:52.876
and he couldn't tell you,
"here, you go play with this,

43:53.180 --> 43:55.592
it's going to work,
go play with this, it isn't."

43:55.891 --> 43:57.222
this was russ' company.

43:57.518 --> 43:59.133
russ loved japan,
he loved the culture.

43:59.437 --> 44:01.519
and he said, "you know mark,
i think that's a great idea. "

44:01.814 --> 44:05.022
because he was so cutting edge.
you know, he was so hip.

44:05.317 --> 44:06.807
he was always taking
that next step forward

44:07.111 --> 44:08.396
before the forward was there.

44:08.696 --> 44:10.527
[mark] I saw this location
and loved it.

44:10.823 --> 44:12.905
called russ,
and I think he was in japan

44:13.200 --> 44:14.656
within two weeks
to look at the location.

44:17.371 --> 44:20.408
it took six to eight months
of legal wrangling to do this,

44:20.708 --> 44:22.744
because it hadn't
been done before.

44:23.043 --> 44:26.160
in japan, in order
to open up a business
you had to have a partner.

44:26.464 --> 44:29.581
there was restaurants,
shakey's pizza parlors

44:29.884 --> 44:32.842
and mcdonald's,
but those were all franchises.

44:33.137 --> 44:35.924
there was no retail
establishment in japan

44:36.223 --> 44:37.963
wholly owned
by an american company.

44:38.267 --> 44:40.508
it was something nobody else
had ever done, for christ sake.

44:40.811 --> 44:44.474
this was a 3,000 year old
country and nobody
could ever think

44:44.773 --> 44:46.104
of another american company

44:46.400 --> 44:49.062
opening a retail store
without a japanese partner.

44:49.361 --> 44:53.946
[rock music playing]

44:59.872 --> 45:02.079
[mark]getting all of
the racking, the records,

45:02.374 --> 45:04.080
the employees,
everything in place,

45:04.376 --> 45:06.867
that went without a hitch.
that was no problem.

45:07.171 --> 45:08.331
the hardest part, once again,

45:08.631 --> 45:10.667
was all of
the legal maneuvering

45:10.966 --> 45:13.002
that had to go on
just to open the store.

45:13.302 --> 45:16.635
but he did open up
the shibuya store.

45:16.931 --> 45:18.671
[mark]literally,
the morning we opened,

45:18.974 --> 45:20.555
we had over 300 or 400 people

45:20.851 --> 45:22.182
standing in line
to get in to the store.

45:24.230 --> 45:27.188
[russ]people were literally
squash ed against the door,

45:27.483 --> 45:29.940
waiting to get in,
and they poured in.

45:30.236 --> 45:31.066
you never saw anything like it.

45:31.362 --> 45:33.569
i mean, it was amazing.

45:33.864 --> 45:35.274
[mark] I remember,
the store was packed

45:35.574 --> 45:37.110
from the moment
we opened till we closed,

45:37.409 --> 45:40.276
we did like 65,
70 grand that day.

45:40.579 --> 45:42.535
it was like that
for the first month

45:42.831 --> 45:44.947
the store was open.
that store was just

45:45.251 --> 45:47.412
a huge success from day one.

45:47.711 --> 45:51.454
the japanese culture was
really into american music,

45:51.757 --> 45:54.043
and the fact that it was
an american import

45:54.343 --> 45:56.629
and not a japanese pressed...

45:56.929 --> 45:58.294
it wasn't the eagles
pressed in japan,

45:58.597 --> 46:00.133
it was the eagles
made in the united states

46:00.432 --> 46:01.672
brought to japan and sold,

46:01.976 --> 46:06.140
and that whole vibe
really sold well.

46:06.438 --> 46:07.678
we just happened
to literally be

46:07.982 --> 46:09.222
at the right place,
at the right time.

46:09.525 --> 46:11.937
you want to call that luck?
then call it luck.

46:12.236 --> 46:13.521
[interviewer]
what would you call it?

46:13.821 --> 46:14.901
luck. ha!

46:15.197 --> 46:16.812
[rock music playing]

46:19.493 --> 46:23.202
we weren't shoving americana
down japanese th roats,
for god's sakes,

46:23.497 --> 46:25.954
it was a culture,
it was a music culture.

46:26.250 --> 46:29.993
[russ]so he went and found
a second location in yokohama.

46:30.296 --> 46:32.082
he got it, we put it together,

46:32.381 --> 46:35.043
opened that damn thing,
and it was a success, heh.

46:35.342 --> 46:37.048
all we had to do
was open the doors.

46:37.344 --> 46:39.630
people flocked in the joint.

46:39.930 --> 46:42.216
expansion was obviously,
once ya do it,

46:42.516 --> 46:45.053
russ can't wait to do it again.

46:45.352 --> 46:46.888
[russ]
so then we started finding

46:47.187 --> 46:49.018
these kind of stores
all over the country,

46:49.315 --> 46:51.772
one right after another.

46:52.067 --> 46:54.228
[mark]and I think russ,
seeing the success it was

46:54.528 --> 46:56.814
globally, or nationally,
or internationally,

46:57.114 --> 46:59.196
i actually think
that gave him the impetus

46:59.491 --> 47:01.152
to move to new york.

47:01.452 --> 47:03.818
[jim urie]
first met russ solomon
in the early '803.

47:04.121 --> 47:06.282
at that point, I was
the new york branch manager

47:06.582 --> 47:08.368
for what is now sony music,

47:08.667 --> 47:10.703
it was called cbs records
at the time, and of course,

47:11.003 --> 47:13.244
everyone knew
about Tower Records,

47:13.547 --> 47:17.506
but it was not an east coast
phenomenon, at that point.

47:17.801 --> 47:20.258
[russ]we started with
a conversation I was having

47:20.554 --> 47:22.761
at the narm convention
in florida.

47:23.057 --> 47:25.218
we were talking about,
"gosh, you know,

47:25.517 --> 47:27.473
"i'd love to open
a classical store in new york

47:27.770 --> 47:31.103
because that's the place where
people like classical music."

47:31.398 --> 47:33.013
russ called up and said,

47:33.317 --> 47:35.228
"hey guys, I want you
to come to my office."

47:35.527 --> 47:37.233
we go in there, and russ says,

47:37.529 --> 47:39.394
"how would you like
to open the store

47:39.698 --> 47:43.486
"in the middle of the hippest
city in the united states

47:43.786 --> 47:45.117
by a college?"

47:45.412 --> 47:46.993
we had no idea
what he was talking about.

47:47.289 --> 47:50.577
and we go down into the bowels
of lower manhattan

47:50.876 --> 47:52.537
to the village,
4th and broadway.

47:52.836 --> 47:54.952
[steve nikkel]there wasn't even
a particular neighborhood.

47:55.255 --> 47:57.496
we started calling it
the village, and it became
part of the village.

47:57.800 --> 48:00.166
but it really wasn't part
of the village. [chuckles]

48:00.469 --> 48:03.506
but you spend enough money
in marketing and things happen.

48:03.806 --> 48:05.262
it was terrible,
it was like I kind of thought,

48:05.557 --> 48:08.094
"what the fuck is he thinking?"

48:08.394 --> 48:10.259
there was a dead dog
in the gutter.

48:10.562 --> 48:14.146
i'm in shock,
i thought we were...

48:14.441 --> 48:15.647
in the bowels of hell.

48:15.943 --> 48:17.604
[russ]
and it was really cheap rent.

48:17.903 --> 48:19.814
i mean the whole deal
was like 10 bucks a foot.

48:20.114 --> 48:21.570
[jim]literally, there was
nothing else there.

48:21.865 --> 48:24.402
empty office buildings,
empty storefronts,

48:24.702 --> 48:27.444
there was nothing around it.
i can't emphasize that enough.

48:27.746 --> 48:29.782
there was nothing
around it at all.

48:30.082 --> 48:33.074
you know, it was like
a massive four stories,

48:33.377 --> 48:34.662
m ezzanines,
escalators, you know,

48:34.962 --> 48:38.250
very, very expensive
store to build. very risky.

48:38.549 --> 48:40.460
[russ]we took it,
and then we fixed it up

48:40.759 --> 48:42.545
everybody thought
we were totally crazy.

48:42.845 --> 48:46.053
that nobody would ever go
to broadway and buy records,

48:46.348 --> 48:49.556
and we open up, and the people
are lined up to get in.

48:49.852 --> 48:52.093
[jim]and here is this
cavernous store,

48:52.396 --> 48:55.058
half a block footprint,
four stories,

48:55.357 --> 48:56.972
had an elevator it was so tall.

48:57.276 --> 48:59.517
god knows how much inventory
was in there.

48:59.820 --> 49:01.310
it looked fantastic,
of course,

49:01.613 --> 49:03.069
the vinyl with
the 12-inch artwork.

49:03.365 --> 49:05.105
i mean, it looked great,
and it was everywhere.

49:05.409 --> 49:07.274
their singles department alone

49:07.578 --> 49:09.569
was probably bigger
than any other store

49:09.872 --> 49:12.113
in my whole new york
tri-state area.

49:12.416 --> 49:14.498
and it wasn't three years later

49:14.793 --> 49:18.661
when that whole part of town
became vibrant again.

49:18.964 --> 49:22.172
Tower Records opening there
literally revived

49:22.468 --> 49:27.508
those eight or ten
square blocks of manhattan.

49:27.806 --> 49:30.047
everybody that worked there
was a character,

49:30.350 --> 49:31.180
but russ was the face

49:31.477 --> 49:33.513
of the company in every way.

49:33.812 --> 49:35.803
i worked at polygram records
in new york.

49:36.106 --> 49:38.313
as happens in any
entertainment company

49:38.609 --> 49:41.225
there was a change at the top
and so a whole bunch of us
got blown out as a result.

49:41.528 --> 49:44.440
new management coming in.
i was senior vice president
of marketing.

49:44.740 --> 49:47.607
and it feels pretty bad
to get fired.

49:47.910 --> 49:49.400
and you're on the outside
of this business

49:49.703 --> 49:51.284
you've been in your whole life,

49:51.580 --> 49:53.912
and your phone's not ringing,

49:54.208 --> 49:56.494
you worry about your family,
and all these things.

49:56.794 --> 49:58.659
russ used to have
this big christmas party

49:58.962 --> 50:00.327
in his major markets,

50:00.631 --> 50:02.371
and the one in new york
was really big.

50:02.674 --> 50:04.039
probably 500 people.

50:04.343 --> 50:05.833
and out of the blue
i get an invitation

50:06.136 --> 50:07.717
to go to the christmas party
at my home,

50:08.013 --> 50:09.503
and I was, of course
happy about that,

50:09.807 --> 50:11.092
i thought,
" do I really want to go

50:11.391 --> 50:12.301
have people looking at me,
feeling sorry?"

50:12.601 --> 50:13.340
but I finally decided to go.

50:13.644 --> 50:15.305
and I go in that night,

50:15.604 --> 50:18.516
and you sort of walked in
and walked down some stai rs.

50:18.816 --> 50:20.306
when you first walk in
you could see the whole place,

50:20.609 --> 50:22.895
and it was huge,
and shoulder to shoulder.

50:23.195 --> 50:25.481
and russ was like
the pied piper in the middle.

50:25.781 --> 50:28.363
where russ went,
there were throngs of people.

50:28.659 --> 50:30.115
as russ made his way
around the room,

50:30.410 --> 50:31.650
there was always
a throng of people.

50:31.954 --> 50:34.036
everybody wanted to shake
his hand, touch him.

50:34.331 --> 50:35.286
so, umm...

50:38.293 --> 50:39.123
i, uh...

50:40.504 --> 50:41.960
i finally shook his hand,

50:42.256 --> 50:44.542
said, "hi, thanks for
inviting me", whatever.

50:44.842 --> 50:47.458
he leaned over to me
and he said,

50:47.761 --> 50:51.049
"a couple of us are going out
for dinner afterward.
do you wanna go?"

50:52.474 --> 50:54.180
[choked up]
and, uh...

50:54.476 --> 50:56.137
let me start that again.

50:58.355 --> 51:00.346
"a couple of us are going out
to dinner. do you wanna go?"

51:00.649 --> 51:03.766
and I said,
"well, golly yeah, russ,
if you really want to have me."

51:04.069 --> 51:05.900
so he told me where and I went.

51:06.196 --> 51:08.187
and it was russ,
and four other people, and me.

51:13.453 --> 51:14.533
and, uh...

51:16.331 --> 51:17.411
and at that moment in my life,

51:17.708 --> 51:20.745
that meant... a lot.

51:22.546 --> 51:24.377
because I was down.

51:24.673 --> 51:26.755
and that russ solomon
would care enough,

51:27.050 --> 51:29.132
and do that
personal little touch...

51:32.055 --> 51:34.296
means something to me now,
20 some years later.

51:38.353 --> 51:41.060
he could have used it, I mean,
most guys would have used it

51:41.356 --> 51:42.937
as a business opportunity
and grabbed

51:43.233 --> 51:45.019
a couple record company
presidents and whatever,

51:45.319 --> 51:47.480
instead of
some out of work guy.

51:47.779 --> 51:50.316
but that's not the way
russ sees life.

51:58.332 --> 52:00.493
[Heidi] The whole magic
of Tower as a chain

52:00.792 --> 52:02.453
was that it was a chain
of independent stores.

52:02.753 --> 52:04.368
book stores as well
as the record stores.

52:04.671 --> 52:06.411
so when you walked
into a Tower Record store,

52:06.715 --> 52:08.626
you thought it was
the only one on the planet.

52:08.926 --> 52:11.542
the l.a. people always
thought the l.a. store
was the first store.

52:11.845 --> 52:14.086
the new yorkers always thought
the new york store was.

52:14.389 --> 52:16.926
the san francisco people thought
that their store was.

52:17.225 --> 52:18.840
because they all had
the individual flavor

52:19.144 --> 52:21.305
of the people who ran it
and who worked there.

52:21.605 --> 52:22.890
which made them very unique.

52:23.190 --> 52:26.307
there was no cookie cutter
going on at all.

52:26.610 --> 52:28.601
[steve nikkel]until we got
into some of the larger markets

52:28.904 --> 52:30.565
on the east coast,
then we started buying

52:30.864 --> 52:33.901
national tv for ads,
so we became a national brand.

52:34.201 --> 52:35.190
but you had to have

52:35.494 --> 52:36.984
the credibility
in the larger markets

52:37.287 --> 52:39.403
before you could go
into the suburbs.

52:39.706 --> 52:41.822
probably in about late '703,

52:42.125 --> 52:44.912
we established our own
advertising department.

52:45.212 --> 52:47.453
that was chris hopson
who ran it.

52:47.756 --> 52:49.542
farrace was just
working in there

52:49.841 --> 52:51.923
as one of the advertising
people, the assistants.

52:52.219 --> 52:54.585
farrace also was
one of these thinkers.

52:54.888 --> 52:56.378
and he came to me
one day and says,

52:56.682 --> 52:58.172
"we ought to have
a magazine for Tower,

52:58.475 --> 53:00.386
i've got an idea
what to call it: pulse."

53:00.686 --> 53:02.017
i said, "great, let's do it."

53:03.563 --> 53:05.224
[mike farrace]
working with chris,

53:05.524 --> 53:07.856
we hammered out this way
that the magazine would exist

53:08.151 --> 53:09.687
and when people
advertised in it,

53:09.987 --> 53:11.477
they would get a sale price
in the store,

53:11.780 --> 53:13.020
positioning in a rack,

53:13.323 --> 53:15.484
just the things
that really gave it the teeth.

53:15.784 --> 53:17.820
[steve]pulse was another
credibility thing for us.

53:18.120 --> 53:19.826
we could not only sell music,

53:20.122 --> 53:22.113
but we could write about it,
we could communicate about it.

53:22.416 --> 53:24.953
[Springsteen] I mean,
there was nothing and no one

53:25.252 --> 53:28.210
with the exception
of your rock fanzines

53:28.505 --> 53:32.418
and small columns in maybe
a few of the major newspapers

53:32.718 --> 53:35.004
that were interested
in what you were doing.

53:35.303 --> 53:36.839
there weren't that
many people interested

53:37.139 --> 53:39.130
in what 25Â—yearÂ—old kids
were doing with music.

53:39.433 --> 53:42.721
so you made your record,
you gave a few interviews

53:43.020 --> 53:46.308
to music publications,
and some daily newspapers,

53:46.606 --> 53:48.267
that was all there was to do.

53:48.567 --> 53:50.728
[steve]it was a very credible
music magazine,

53:51.028 --> 53:52.814
and it was a national
music magazine

53:53.113 --> 53:54.853
because of all
the markets we were in.

53:55.157 --> 53:58.445
and the magazine grew and
it was a really good magazine.

53:58.744 --> 54:00.029
but it was a great idea.

54:00.328 --> 54:01.943
I remember him
saying more than once,

54:02.247 --> 54:03.987
"just don't lose
too much money on it."

54:04.291 --> 54:05.872
and try to make something.

54:06.168 --> 54:09.331
it was the first time he really
focused on an idea I had.

54:09.629 --> 54:12.371
[russ]you'd listen
to the people who had ideas.

54:12.674 --> 54:13.914
the kids in the store,

54:14.217 --> 54:16.674
who I say invented
all kinds of ideas.

54:16.970 --> 54:18.506
everything we ever did
was invented

54:18.805 --> 54:20.386
by the kids in the store.

54:20.682 --> 54:23.765
the art on the walls,
the way they displayed things.

54:24.061 --> 54:27.224
their attitude about what to buy
and what not to buy.

54:27.522 --> 54:30.184
was all things happening
at the store level.

54:30.484 --> 54:32.816
the whole "no music, no life",
came out of japan.

54:33.111 --> 54:35.022
we adopted it,
brought it in, and used it.

54:35.322 --> 54:36.937
so we're using
their creativity.

54:37.240 --> 54:38.400
going,
"wow, this is interesting."

54:38.700 --> 54:40.156
or, "ah, that's too dark."

54:40.452 --> 54:41.817
and i'm going,
"no it's not, it's fun."

54:42.120 --> 54:43.530
no music, no life,
in this sort of

54:43.830 --> 54:45.536
snoopy, peanuts kind of script,

54:45.832 --> 54:47.242
i'm going,
"this is very cool."

54:47.542 --> 54:50.955
it was famous for
the record cover paintings

54:51.254 --> 54:53.996
that was jammed
on its walls outside.

54:54.299 --> 54:56.039
[bob delanoy]but that became
prominent.

54:56.343 --> 54:57.708
all of a sudden,
that became the norm

54:58.011 --> 54:59.547
for anywhere we had windows.

54:59.846 --> 55:02.087
they'd expect us
to put some displays.

55:02.390 --> 55:05.803
[springsteen]you aspired
to have your album

55:06.103 --> 55:08.310
part of that big mural
out there, you know.

55:08.605 --> 55:10.596
I mean, the board thing
was really cool,

55:10.899 --> 55:12.981
and then we took it inside
where we had an art dept.

55:13.276 --> 55:15.733
that was all foam core,
it wasn't just people
stapling albums up.

55:16.029 --> 55:17.485
people went to great lengths,

55:17.781 --> 55:20.614
like they'd get that
weird foam cardboard stuff

55:20.909 --> 55:22.865
and make a baby,
and then there's

55:23.161 --> 55:24.867
an actual dollar bill
dangling in front of it,

55:25.163 --> 55:27.028
and it looks like water
behind it, you know,

55:27.332 --> 55:29.869
and when you'd see people go
to that much trouble for you,

55:30.168 --> 55:31.157
for your band,

55:31.461 --> 55:34.248
we were just...
we were just shocked.

55:34.548 --> 55:37.005
I think that really
influenced and enhanced

55:37.300 --> 55:39.507
the experience people had
when they came in the store.

55:39.803 --> 55:41.839
the presentation of music...

55:43.890 --> 55:46.597
was physically exciting.

55:46.893 --> 55:48.224
[steve knopper]
they branded it, they made

55:48.520 --> 55:50.431
those red and yellow
logos and signs.

55:50.730 --> 55:53.096
and turned the idea that this
was your local record store

55:53.400 --> 55:55.265
into a national thing.

55:55.569 --> 55:57.935
[Mike Solomon] Tower was growing
at a faster and faster rate,

55:58.238 --> 55:59.728
was becoming more successful,

56:00.031 --> 56:03.194
and was becoming
more known or renowned.

56:03.493 --> 56:06.576
the employees at Tower
felt proud about that.

56:06.872 --> 56:08.362
we helped each other
make it work.

56:08.665 --> 56:11.623
we tried to get
the person below us promoted

56:11.918 --> 56:12.873
so that they could move on.

56:13.170 --> 56:14.580
I became a store manager.

56:14.880 --> 56:16.620
I became the regional director,

56:16.923 --> 56:18.959
i became vice president
of operations for the USA,

56:19.259 --> 56:20.624
i became vice president
and director

56:20.927 --> 56:22.508
of inÂ—store design
and development.

56:22.804 --> 56:25.045
[stan]we were really getting
into an expansion mode.

56:25.348 --> 56:28.681
it was quite a transition
from being store-centric

56:28.977 --> 56:31.559
to having to look
at the whole picture.

56:31.855 --> 56:34.847
but all those years
weren't wonderful years.

56:35.150 --> 56:36.765
i only remember this
because I was a young guy,

56:37.068 --> 56:38.649
and had to lay some people off
for the first time.

56:38.945 --> 56:41.357
'79, '81, and like '83
were years

56:41.656 --> 56:43.817
where the record companies were
actually laying people off.

56:44.117 --> 56:45.823
rock and roll,
which had been so exciting

56:46.119 --> 56:48.485
just 10 or 15
or 20 years earlier,

56:48.788 --> 56:51.621
kind of got to the point where
it was a little bit stagnant.

56:51.917 --> 56:53.373
the record labels, many of them,

56:53.668 --> 56:56.125
had put all their eggs
into the disco basket.

56:56.421 --> 56:58.707
a lot of radio stations
immediately changed formats

56:59.007 --> 57:01.168
in every big city there were
two or three disco stations

57:01.468 --> 57:03.208
that replaced
other formats of radio,

57:03.511 --> 57:05.593
and I think hurt
as disco didn't sell that well.

57:05.889 --> 57:08.175
there were a lot of layoffs,
record sales went way, way down,

57:08.475 --> 57:10.431
and some in the industry
that were really worried.

57:10.727 --> 57:14.561
it was all disco, and then
disco just one day crashed.

57:14.856 --> 57:17.393
you would up having these
djs to get attention,

57:17.692 --> 57:18.477
take advantage of it.

57:18.777 --> 57:19.812
"disco sucks, man."

57:20.111 --> 57:21.976
and so there was a recession.

57:22.280 --> 57:25.488
three things happened
that pulled the music industry

57:25.784 --> 57:27.820
out of its recession,
out of its doldrums.

57:28.119 --> 57:29.905
[engine roars]

57:30.205 --> 57:33.618
[electric guitar playing rock]

57:33.917 --> 57:35.202
one thing was mtv.

57:35.502 --> 57:37.117
turn it on,
leave it on.

57:37.420 --> 57:40.253
america, see the music
you want to see.

57:40.548 --> 57:42.084
i want my mtv.

57:42.384 --> 57:43.965
[steve]artists who'd been
somewhat successful

57:44.261 --> 57:46.843
could add a whole new visual
part of their careers.

57:47.138 --> 57:48.628
if you got your video on mtv,

57:48.932 --> 57:51.799
that directly had
a huge impact on sales.

57:52.102 --> 57:53.387
hi, mtv.

57:53.687 --> 57:55.097
[jim] I can remember clearly
signing off on

57:55.397 --> 57:58.685
video budgets
that were $700, $800,000.

57:58.984 --> 58:01.396
it was all important
that we get that thing on mtv

58:01.695 --> 58:03.105
and if we did,
boy we were off to the races.

58:03.405 --> 58:06.238
call your cable company and say,

58:06.533 --> 58:08.023
"i want my mtv!"

58:08.326 --> 58:11.193
the second thing was michael
jackson's thriller album.

58:11.496 --> 58:13.828
in the record industry,
there's a saying,
"hits save everything."

58:14.124 --> 58:16.365
and so thriller was
the proverbial rising tide

58:16.668 --> 58:17.953
that lifted all the boats.

58:18.253 --> 58:20.289
so many people went
into record stores,

58:20.588 --> 58:23.045
including Tower, tens of
millions of them at a time.

58:23.341 --> 58:24.956
and when they were in there,
they'd say,

58:25.260 --> 58:26.796
"oh, how about also
this lionel richie album,

58:27.095 --> 58:28.505
"and how about
this madonna album,

58:28.805 --> 58:30.841
and how about this springsteen,
and prince album?ii

58:31.141 --> 58:32.426
then the whole thing
started to lift.

58:32.726 --> 58:34.011
and then the third
and final thing,

58:34.311 --> 58:35.892
which was much more
of a prolonged thing

58:36.187 --> 58:38.143
was the adoption of the cd.

58:40.859 --> 58:43.145
it's hard to remember now,
because they seem
so antiquated,

58:43.445 --> 58:45.310
but cds for a while were cool.

58:45.613 --> 58:47.774
they were shiny and silver,
and state of the art,

58:48.074 --> 58:49.314
and they sounded perfect.

58:49.617 --> 58:51.073
they sounded pristine,
and that was something

58:51.369 --> 58:53.451
that we couldn't get
from our big, cumbersome lps.

58:53.747 --> 58:55.703
that was exciting
because it was digital

58:55.999 --> 58:58.741
and as much as I like
the sound of lps,

58:59.044 --> 59:01.080
the ticks and pops when
you were listening to classical

59:01.379 --> 59:03.210
used to just drive me
up the wall.

59:03.506 --> 59:05.497
so this thing was coming out,
and you'd go,

59:05.800 --> 59:08.587
"okay, well how do
we explain this to people?"

59:08.887 --> 59:10.423
how do we tell them
there's a whole,

59:10.722 --> 59:12.337
not only that there's a whole
new technology out there,

59:12.640 --> 59:14.471
but there's also
a reason to buy it,

59:14.768 --> 59:18.807
because there are enough cds
out there for you to buy.

59:19.105 --> 59:20.140
but you didn't know

59:20.440 --> 59:21.850
if the people
would adopt it or not.

59:22.150 --> 59:24.607
the executives at labels
resisted the cd,

59:24.903 --> 59:26.109
they wanted
no part of it at all.

59:26.404 --> 59:29.191
they were worried
that it'd create piracy.

59:29.491 --> 59:31.072
but russ persevered
th rough that,

59:31.368 --> 59:35.953
and he was the first, biggest,
best champion of the cd.

59:36.247 --> 59:37.737
[russ]it is so clean.

59:38.041 --> 59:40.532
i'm very conscious
of high quality sound.

59:40.835 --> 59:42.700
he always said that
that was going to be

59:43.004 --> 59:44.369
the savior of the retail store.

59:44.672 --> 59:46.754
these new, innovative,
high end,

59:47.050 --> 59:48.836
super great sounding discs.

59:49.135 --> 59:50.215
[steve knopper]
everybody, it turns out,

59:50.512 --> 59:52.002
was getting tired of the lp,

59:52.305 --> 59:54.296
and they were ready to replace
their record collections

59:54.599 --> 59:56.715
on this more expensive product
called the cd.

59:57.018 --> 59:58.679
i mean that was a huge piece
of the record business

59:58.978 --> 01:00:01.469
was people replacing
their catalogs with cds.

01:00:01.773 --> 01:00:03.809
look at this cool new thing.

01:00:04.109 --> 01:00:05.645
where can I buy it?
Tower Records.

01:00:08.905 --> 01:00:10.065
as an experiment,
the Tower store

01:00:10.365 --> 01:00:11.650
on sunset boulevard
in los angeles

01:00:11.950 --> 01:00:13.611
has installed
a bin full of cds.

01:00:13.910 --> 01:00:15.446
[steve knopper]they realized
the cd was much more expensive.

01:00:15.745 --> 01:00:17.656
and it would push up
that price point

01:00:17.956 --> 01:00:19.947
up to maybe $15.99 or $16.99,

01:00:20.250 --> 01:00:22.161
which was a god send
for the record industry

01:00:22.460 --> 01:00:24.826
at that time,
and Tower took advantage of it.

