[male tv announcer]
all the music is stuck

01:03:18.845 --> 01:03:20.585
in this completely
warped galaxy,

01:03:20.888 --> 01:03:22.469
but then Tower goes
and gets it back,

01:03:22.765 --> 01:03:25.051
and opens stores
all over your planet.

01:03:25.351 --> 01:03:28.809
Tower Records, more
music for less money.

01:03:29.105 --> 01:03:31.187
[steve knopper]and it was
just overwhelmingly big.
everybody knew the logo.

01:03:31.482 --> 01:03:32.892
everybody knew the
red and yellow bag.

01:03:33.192 --> 01:03:34.523
[man]when the digital
revolution came,

01:03:34.819 --> 01:03:36.150
you know the record
business jumped on it

01:03:36.446 --> 01:03:40.485
with the cd,
not realizing that they were

01:03:40.783 --> 01:03:42.398
really causing their own demise.

01:03:42.702 --> 01:03:44.909
[Knopper] But I definitely think
that Tower was optimistic,

01:03:45.204 --> 01:03:46.159
and they felt like
the good times would last

01:03:46.456 --> 01:03:47.571
for a good long time.

01:03:47.874 --> 01:03:49.364
i mean they expanded
during this period.

01:03:49.667 --> 01:03:51.623
[mike]well, by the early '9os,
we were having

01:03:51.919 --> 01:03:53.910
pretty good success
in our foreign operations.

01:03:54.213 --> 01:03:55.544
again, it was driven by japan,

01:03:55.840 --> 01:03:58.001
which was extremely profitable.

01:03:58.301 --> 01:04:01.919
maybe more so than the
domestic company in america.

01:04:02.221 --> 01:04:03.836
[russ]we moved
the old shibuya store

01:04:04.140 --> 01:04:06.176
to this new shibuya store,
it was an eight story building.

01:04:06.476 --> 01:04:08.182
84,000 feet.

01:04:08.478 --> 01:04:10.560
each floor was
a segmented store.

01:04:10.855 --> 01:04:13.562
and the place was doing
hundreds of hundreds

01:04:13.858 --> 01:04:15.189
of thousands
of dollars a month.

01:04:15.485 --> 01:04:18.397
i mean, it was a huge
success. [chuckles]

01:04:18.696 --> 01:04:19.776
you couldn't stop 'em.

01:04:20.073 --> 01:04:22.940
it gave us a lot of confidence.

01:04:23.242 --> 01:04:24.527
somebody came
from england and said,

01:04:24.827 --> 01:04:26.112
"why don't you
have a store in england?"

01:04:26.412 --> 01:04:27.902
howdy, i'm russ solomon.

01:04:28.206 --> 01:04:30.322
i want to take this opportunity
to welcome all of you

01:04:30.625 --> 01:04:32.161
to our little
spot in central london,

01:04:32.460 --> 01:04:34.200
and I hope you're going
to have a great time tonight

01:04:34.504 --> 01:04:38.122
seeing what is tonight,
the marriage of wembley
and Tower.

01:04:38.424 --> 01:04:39.709
two great names
in entertainment.

01:04:40.009 --> 01:04:41.499
so drink up
and have a great time.

01:04:41.803 --> 01:04:43.418
i'm doin' it.

01:04:43.721 --> 01:04:45.803
[russ] and then in japan,
the guy that we sent to japan

01:04:46.099 --> 01:04:49.387
a few years later, makes a
contact with somebody in taiwan

01:04:49.686 --> 01:04:50.892
to make a partnership

01:04:51.187 --> 01:04:53.303
for hong kong and taiwan
and singapore.

01:04:53.606 --> 01:04:55.972
the company was
really getting big.

01:04:58.820 --> 01:05:01.277
[steve nikkel]we were doing
business on a very high level.

01:05:01.572 --> 01:05:03.108
but you never escaped
this thing that

01:05:03.408 --> 01:05:05.239
wow, it's like,
i'm sitting in an ex-pat bar

01:05:05.535 --> 01:05:07.366
at 2:00 in the morning
in taipei,

01:05:07.662 --> 01:05:10.074
you know,
and i'm from sacramento.

01:05:10.373 --> 01:05:11.408
how cool is this?

01:05:11.708 --> 01:05:14.996
moving to countries
outside of japan

01:05:15.294 --> 01:05:16.283
was a risk.

01:05:16.587 --> 01:05:17.417
they expanded
in latin america,

01:05:17.714 --> 01:05:20.046
in asia, and all over the place.

01:05:20.341 --> 01:05:22.548
[woman] can you give
the fans message tonight?

01:05:22.844 --> 01:05:24.675
no music, no life.

01:05:24.971 --> 01:05:27.257
[mike]we were becoming
famous worldwide,

01:05:27.557 --> 01:05:29.047
and we enjoyed that.

01:05:29.350 --> 01:05:30.339
why, I suppose
it stroked our egos

01:05:30.643 --> 01:05:31.428
to a certain point.

01:05:31.728 --> 01:05:32.934
it was fucking awesome.

01:05:33.229 --> 01:05:35.561
i mean, come on. [laughs]

01:05:35.857 --> 01:05:39.315
i mean, my gosh,
it was a mind blower.

01:05:39.610 --> 01:05:40.565
it was really fun.

01:05:40.862 --> 01:05:42.773
we got to know
more about music

01:05:43.072 --> 01:05:45.154
going in to mexico city,
going in to colombia,

01:05:45.450 --> 01:05:47.486
and buenos aires,
it allowed us to know

01:05:47.785 --> 01:05:49.491
a lot more about latin music.

01:05:49.787 --> 01:05:51.948
but we weren't really successful

01:05:52.248 --> 01:05:54.739
in any of the other countries
we went into.

01:05:55.042 --> 01:05:56.202
therein lies the tale.

01:05:56.502 --> 01:05:58.288
you know sometimes,
i guess, one can get

01:05:58.588 --> 01:06:00.249
a little too big
for their britches.

01:06:00.548 --> 01:06:02.379
like I said,
there was this culture

01:06:02.675 --> 01:06:04.711
that was growing
that wherever we wanted

01:06:05.011 --> 01:06:06.922
to put a store,
build it and they will come,

01:06:07.221 --> 01:06:08.586
field of dreams bullshit.

01:06:08.890 --> 01:06:10.881
there was no due diligence,
for christ sakes,

01:06:11.184 --> 01:06:14.176
done on buenos aires
or mexico city.

01:06:14.479 --> 01:06:17.141
i said borrow
all that damn money.

01:06:17.440 --> 01:06:20.227
i'm as guilty about
that as anybody else.

01:06:20.526 --> 01:06:23.017
i'm stupid for saying yes

01:06:23.321 --> 01:06:25.061
to partnerships in argentina

01:06:25.364 --> 01:06:27.320
even though I didn't
totally believe in 'em.

01:06:27.617 --> 01:06:30.700
[mike solomon]bud did not want
the company to go in to
so much debt.

01:06:30.995 --> 01:06:32.781
he would succumb
to the pressure that russ

01:06:33.080 --> 01:06:36.038
put on him,
although he was happy enough,

01:06:36.334 --> 01:06:37.449
especially because he was making

01:06:37.752 --> 01:06:38.832
a lot of money, personally.

01:06:39.128 --> 01:06:40.334
if you look
at the music industry

01:06:40.630 --> 01:06:42.791
at any given point
during that period

01:06:43.090 --> 01:06:45.957
from '84 to 2000,
you wouldn't really go,

01:06:46.260 --> 01:06:48.672
"oh no, there's choppy
waters on the horizon."

01:06:48.971 --> 01:06:50.256
russ, what about
these new technologies

01:06:50.556 --> 01:06:53.889
like the mini disc, dcc,
or beaming music and video

01:06:54.185 --> 01:06:55.345
right in to my house?

01:06:55.645 --> 01:06:57.260
are my cds history,
and will your inventory

01:06:57.563 --> 01:06:59.019
at Tower become obsolete?

01:06:59.315 --> 01:07:00.521
there's so many new technologies

01:07:00.817 --> 01:07:02.307
we simply get
involved with them.

01:07:02.610 --> 01:07:03.690
we get involved with them

01:07:03.986 --> 01:07:05.522
at the early part
of their development

01:07:05.822 --> 01:07:08.154
and we grow with 'em,
or when they die,

01:07:08.449 --> 01:07:10.781
we throw them out like d.a.t.

01:07:11.077 --> 01:07:12.658
as for the whole concept
of beaming something

01:07:12.954 --> 01:07:16.412
in to one's home,
that may come along someday,

01:07:16.707 --> 01:07:18.538
that's for sure,
but it will come along

01:07:18.835 --> 01:07:20.575
over a long period of time,
and we'll be able

01:07:20.878 --> 01:07:22.493
to deal with it
and change our focus

01:07:22.797 --> 01:07:24.412
and change the way
we do business

01:07:24.715 --> 01:07:27.127
to deal with the
situation as it really is.

01:07:27.426 --> 01:07:28.632
as far as your cd collection,

01:07:28.928 --> 01:07:31.214
and our cd inventory
for that matter,

01:07:31.514 --> 01:07:34.176
it's going to be around
for a long, long time,
believe me.

01:07:34.475 --> 01:07:35.965
[russ]when you look back
on all your mistakes,

01:07:36.269 --> 01:07:37.725
and you make 'em,
that's for sure,

01:07:38.020 --> 01:07:40.261
it just, it catches up with ya,

01:07:40.565 --> 01:07:42.101
is what the truth of it is.

01:07:42.400 --> 01:07:45.267
you think you're
going to be all right,

01:07:45.570 --> 01:07:46.730
and when it catches up with ya,

01:07:47.029 --> 01:07:49.395
then it's too late
to do anything about it.

01:07:49.699 --> 01:07:51.405
[mike solomon]the business had
grown significantly.

01:07:51.701 --> 01:07:53.362
it was an
international business.

01:07:53.661 --> 01:07:56.778
sales were running close
to a billion dollars
by that time,

01:07:57.081 --> 01:07:59.743
and bud the accountant
was possibly

01:08:00.042 --> 01:08:01.248
a little bit over his head.

01:08:01.544 --> 01:08:03.910
we had to hire a guy
from the outside.

01:08:04.213 --> 01:08:05.453
fellow by the name
of dee searson.

01:08:05.756 --> 01:08:08.418
[russ]because I had
complete trust in bud,

01:08:08.718 --> 01:08:10.583
i had also complete
trust with dee.

01:08:10.887 --> 01:08:13.253
[mike solomon]by the early
19903, the relationship

01:08:13.556 --> 01:08:16.593
between bud and russ had
become a little bit strained.

01:08:16.893 --> 01:08:19.930
bud stopped going
to the daily lunches,

01:08:20.229 --> 01:08:21.514
they were giving him ulcers.

01:08:21.814 --> 01:08:26.148
bud's job became less
and less important.

01:08:26.444 --> 01:08:27.774
he finally had to leave.

01:08:28.069 --> 01:08:32.404
so it was around 1995
that bud decided to retire.

01:08:32.700 --> 01:08:35.533
russ will,
even to this day, will say

01:08:35.828 --> 01:08:37.613
that that's one of the things
that went wrong

01:08:37.913 --> 01:08:41.532
when bud was kind of eased out.

01:08:41.834 --> 01:08:43.790
[rudy danzinger]! think bud
was that kind of person

01:08:44.086 --> 01:08:45.622
they felt as though
something's going to happen.

01:08:45.921 --> 01:08:47.662
the company won't,
will not be the same.

01:08:47.965 --> 01:08:51.082
when bud left,
dee took over as the cfo.

01:08:51.385 --> 01:08:53.671
[russ]i'm developing a company
and expanding a company,

01:08:53.970 --> 01:08:57.259
he's managing the money,
and it was a surprise to me

01:08:57.558 --> 01:08:59.048
that I couldn't
use all that money

01:08:59.352 --> 01:09:00.716
to open new stores.

01:09:01.020 --> 01:09:02.885
[mike solomon]dee was put
on a mission to go out

01:09:03.189 --> 01:09:06.898
and get money
by Tower selling bonds.

01:09:07.193 --> 01:09:10.401
well, it made it
easier for Tower

01:09:10.696 --> 01:09:12.778
to borrow more money.

01:09:13.073 --> 01:09:14.689
things became much more tense.

01:09:14.992 --> 01:09:16.528
we had pressure from creditors,

01:09:16.827 --> 01:09:19.033
from bond holders, from banks,

01:09:19.330 --> 01:09:21.867
and there was pressure
in the business in general.

01:09:22.166 --> 01:09:24.497
a perfect storm
of events was developing

01:09:24.794 --> 01:09:27.376
in the music
industry as a whole.

01:09:27.671 --> 01:09:30.334
[jim urie]we'd gone from vinyl
singles, to cassette singles,

01:09:30.633 --> 01:09:33.045
to cd singles,
but we cut that out

01:09:33.344 --> 01:09:35.426
because we felt
like, rightfully so,

01:09:35.720 --> 01:09:36.756
why were we letting people buy

01:09:37.055 --> 01:09:38.341
the best song off an album,

01:09:38.640 --> 01:09:40.881
let's just not make
that available,

01:09:41.185 --> 01:09:42.390
and they'll have
to buy the album.

01:09:42.687 --> 01:09:44.051
and at that day and time,
it was true.

01:09:44.354 --> 01:09:46.345
an eventually,
i think people were kind of

01:09:46.649 --> 01:09:47.889
crying foul about that,

01:09:48.192 --> 01:09:50.808
like okay, I like a couple
of britney spears songs,

01:09:51.112 --> 01:09:53.694
but do I really want to buy
her whole record for $18?

01:09:53.990 --> 01:09:55.355
you know,
it was the peak of that.

01:09:55.658 --> 01:09:57.569
[russ]there was no need
for a whole generation

01:09:57.868 --> 01:09:59.108
of kids to even go
in a record store

01:09:59.412 --> 01:10:00.902
to get their music.

01:10:01.205 --> 01:10:02.786
if you haven't got kids
coming into record stores

01:10:03.082 --> 01:10:05.448
to buy records, heh,
you've lost a lot.

01:10:05.751 --> 01:10:08.458
[jim urie]but then a whole
bunch of other things
started to happen.

01:10:08.754 --> 01:10:11.040
you had
all these mass merchants

01:10:11.340 --> 01:10:12.625
getting
into the music business.

01:10:12.925 --> 01:10:15.507
and there were horrible,
horrible price wars.

01:10:15.803 --> 01:10:18.135
everybody and their brother
started selling cds.

01:10:18.431 --> 01:10:20.763
you know target, wal-mart,
all these companies.

01:10:21.058 --> 01:10:22.639
and they would sell 'em at cost.

01:10:22.935 --> 01:10:26.519
what that took away from us was
the traffic created by the hits.

01:10:26.814 --> 01:10:28.770
if you had a Tower Records
in some market,

01:10:29.066 --> 01:10:30.806
and a best buy moved
across the street,

01:10:31.110 --> 01:10:32.771
the music consumer would go,
"hey, here's the Tower

01:10:33.070 --> 01:10:34.856
on my right where I can
buy the cd for 20 bucks,

01:10:35.156 --> 01:10:36.612
and here's
the best buy on the left

01:10:36.907 --> 01:10:38.192
where I could buy
the cd for 10 bucks."

01:10:38.492 --> 01:10:40.653
even before napster,
that was a big problem.

01:10:40.953 --> 01:10:45.117
the industry as a whole
didn't respond appropriately

01:10:45.416 --> 01:10:46.872
to what was happening.

01:10:47.168 --> 01:10:49.625
what they should have done was
make the records cheaper.

01:10:49.920 --> 01:10:52.002
they could have,
but they didn't.

01:10:52.298 --> 01:10:54.584
and I remember vividly the very
first story on,

01:10:54.884 --> 01:10:57.375
"what is an mp3?",
you know, that we ever did.

01:10:57.678 --> 01:10:59.259
i wasn't depressed
the first time I saw napster.

01:10:59.555 --> 01:11:01.216
actually, I remember it
very clearly,

01:11:01.515 --> 01:11:04.723
and I went on and there were
800,000 people on it.

01:11:05.019 --> 01:11:06.259
and I thought, "wow,

01:11:06.562 --> 01:11:08.302
this is unbelievable.
this is fantastic."

01:11:08.606 --> 01:11:11.473
i wasn't thinking
that those 800,000 people

01:11:11.776 --> 01:11:12.640
were stealing from me, heh.

01:11:12.943 --> 01:11:14.524
it was the most amazing

01:11:14.820 --> 01:11:16.776
piece of software in history.

01:11:17.073 --> 01:11:18.734
there was community in it.

01:11:19.033 --> 01:11:21.365
you could look at each
others lists, playlists.

01:11:21.660 --> 01:11:22.900
it was just a natural.

01:11:23.204 --> 01:11:25.286
[steve nikkel]
mike farrace literally had

01:11:25.581 --> 01:11:27.867
the first record store online.

01:11:28.167 --> 01:11:29.953
but we didn't know
what to do with it.

01:11:30.252 --> 01:11:32.413
in fact, our store was on aol.

01:11:33.881 --> 01:11:35.246
talk about lame.

01:11:35.549 --> 01:11:37.210
developing that into retail

01:11:37.510 --> 01:11:40.126
wasn't really something
that was on my radar.

01:11:40.429 --> 01:11:42.215
but when you realized
how easy it was

01:11:42.515 --> 01:11:45.473
for people to share files
and just literally

01:11:45.768 --> 01:11:48.510
take music for free,
that's a problem.

01:11:48.813 --> 01:11:50.394
how do you compete with that?

01:11:50.689 --> 01:11:54.147
if you could get coca-cola
for free from your faucet,

01:11:54.443 --> 01:11:55.979
you wouldn't buy
a bottle of coca-cola.

01:11:56.278 --> 01:11:58.269
on one hand, you go, okay,
well what's the big deal?

01:11:58.572 --> 01:11:59.857
singles are cheap,

01:12:00.157 --> 01:12:01.317
we don't really need that
much money anyway.

01:12:01.617 --> 01:12:03.357
on the other hand,
when napster came out

01:12:03.661 --> 01:12:06.824
the big issue was,
"how do you compete with free?"

01:12:07.123 --> 01:12:08.488
on one hand,
you have all these people

01:12:08.791 --> 01:12:09.871
who are stealing music
for free,

01:12:10.167 --> 01:12:13.250
on the other hand,
we have this $18 cd,

01:12:13.546 --> 01:12:17.038
which is our main product.
not really a balance.

01:12:17.341 --> 01:12:20.048
but if you have a single,
if you have a 99-cent single,

01:12:20.344 --> 01:12:21.584
or a cheap way of,
an alternative way

01:12:21.887 --> 01:12:23.718
of selling music,
that's a little easier

01:12:24.014 --> 01:12:25.470
to compete with free.

01:12:25.766 --> 01:12:27.802
and we of course saw that later
because itunes kicked in,

01:12:28.102 --> 01:12:29.888
and songs cost 99 cents
and it did very well.

01:12:30.187 --> 01:12:32.644
they think music is available
on the computer,

01:12:32.940 --> 01:12:34.146
go google it,

01:12:34.441 --> 01:12:35.977
and they think they can
just get it for free.

01:12:36.277 --> 01:12:38.359
and that was something
that was discussed

01:12:38.654 --> 01:12:40.440
at nauseam with Russ and Tower.

01:12:40.739 --> 01:12:42.525
he believed that there would
always be people

01:12:42.825 --> 01:12:44.861
wanting to buy records
to have a collection,

01:12:45.161 --> 01:12:47.197
a library,
if you will, of product.

01:12:47.496 --> 01:12:49.612
those people died
off and went away,

01:12:49.915 --> 01:12:51.576
and the generation that followed

01:12:51.876 --> 01:12:56.210
believes that having an ipad,
that's your music collection.

01:12:56.505 --> 01:12:58.666
that's what it is today,
and that's the truth.

01:12:58.966 --> 01:13:01.878
there's no records.
go buy a record, are you nuts?

01:13:02.178 --> 01:13:04.590
and so that kind
of started leaving

01:13:04.889 --> 01:13:06.550
the terrestrial retailers behind

01:13:06.849 --> 01:13:07.884
because that kind of stuff,

01:13:08.184 --> 01:13:10.300
it's just too easy,
too convenient.

01:13:10.603 --> 01:13:12.309
i mean I still enjoy
going in to a record store,

01:13:12.605 --> 01:13:14.220
but I can't tell you
the last time I did.

01:13:14.523 --> 01:13:17.606
did the industry push people
a little bit

01:13:17.902 --> 01:13:21.440
to piracy by forcing them
to buy albums

01:13:21.739 --> 01:13:23.024
when they only wanted a song?

01:13:23.324 --> 01:13:24.939
i can't say that that
is true or not true

01:13:25.242 --> 01:13:27.278
but you could certainly
make that argument.

01:13:27.578 --> 01:13:30.411
and so what became apparent
was the music industry
is changing

01:13:30.706 --> 01:13:33.698
and we are not able
to adjust to that change.

01:13:34.001 --> 01:13:36.868
you could couch that as we're
not adjusting to that change,

01:13:37.171 --> 01:13:39.662
or we don't know how
to adjust to that change,

01:13:39.965 --> 01:13:42.456
but I think you're doing
all of those things at once.

01:13:42.760 --> 01:13:45.126
right when...

01:13:45.429 --> 01:13:46.669
we probably could have changed,

01:13:46.972 --> 01:13:49.008
in my mind,
it was out of my control.

01:13:50.726 --> 01:13:53.809
but my getting sick
didn't help matters any.

01:13:54.104 --> 01:13:55.765
in 1998,
a couple of things happened.

01:13:56.065 --> 01:13:59.182
one, my father had

01:13:59.485 --> 01:14:02.522
an eightÂ—way
bypass heart operation,

01:14:02.821 --> 01:14:05.984
and he was out of the picture
most of that year.

01:14:06.283 --> 01:14:08.490
i was appointed ceo.

01:14:08.786 --> 01:14:10.242
russ was kicked up to chairman.

01:14:10.537 --> 01:14:13.119
stanley, chris hopson,
dee searson and i

01:14:13.415 --> 01:14:14.996
were equals,
then all of a sudden,

01:14:15.292 --> 01:14:16.623
i'm kicked up to ceo.

01:14:16.919 --> 01:14:20.002
that created some
strain and difficulty.

01:14:20.297 --> 01:14:23.130
i knew michael somewhat.
i didn't like it.

01:14:23.425 --> 01:14:25.757
he didn't come up from--
you know, the one thing

01:14:26.053 --> 01:14:27.884
that historically that was
about Tower Records,

01:14:28.180 --> 01:14:31.547
is we all started
and came up, and learned it

01:14:31.850 --> 01:14:33.090
by living it, and doing it.

01:14:33.394 --> 01:14:34.759
and that was pretty much
the case

01:14:35.062 --> 01:14:38.896
working for Tower before
i went to law school.

01:14:39.191 --> 01:14:41.773
when I came back to Tower
in 1988,

01:14:42.069 --> 01:14:46.529
i came in as a senior vice
president and legal counsel,

01:14:46.824 --> 01:14:49.236
and I was immediately tagged

01:14:49.535 --> 01:14:51.366
as the boss' son.

01:14:51.662 --> 01:14:54.699
there were people
who wanted to sabotage me.

01:14:54.999 --> 01:14:57.741
[russ] and mike was good,
but the truth of it is,

01:14:58.043 --> 01:14:59.954
he wasn't me,
in the same sense of

01:15:00.254 --> 01:15:03.587
being able to run
what we wanted to run.

01:15:03.882 --> 01:15:05.418
russell had a persona about him

01:15:05.718 --> 01:15:08.505
that people embrace,
michael didn't.

01:15:08.804 --> 01:15:10.510
it was a challenge to...

01:15:12.057 --> 01:15:14.799
...get the trust and cooperation

01:15:15.102 --> 01:15:17.388
of my executive colleagues.

01:15:17.688 --> 01:15:20.680
another thing started
happening around 2000.

01:15:20.983 --> 01:15:22.894
sales were flattening.

01:15:23.193 --> 01:15:26.526
we had had growth
from 1960 to 2000.

01:15:26.822 --> 01:15:28.904
there was never
a year that there was

01:15:29.199 --> 01:15:30.780
no steady growth in sales.

01:15:31.076 --> 01:15:32.782
this became problematic,

01:15:33.078 --> 01:15:36.866
having a large debt
and a large interest payment,

01:15:37.166 --> 01:15:40.784
and that's sort of where
Tower started going down.

01:15:41.086 --> 01:15:43.919
[stan]everything
you've touched worked,

01:15:44.214 --> 01:15:45.875
and then it stops.

01:15:46.175 --> 01:15:47.756
it was just dumb.

01:15:48.052 --> 01:15:49.838
the business plan didn't work.

01:15:50.137 --> 01:15:51.718
there was no population
to support it.

01:15:52.014 --> 01:15:53.174
it's that simple.

01:15:53.474 --> 01:15:55.430
you've borrowed
all this damn money,

01:15:55.726 --> 01:15:57.637
and all of a sudden,
you become aware

01:15:57.936 --> 01:15:59.176
that you've gone too far.

01:15:59.480 --> 01:16:01.186
everything's working
well in japan,

01:16:01.482 --> 01:16:02.722
but because you've lost money

01:16:03.025 --> 01:16:04.435
in all these other places,

01:16:04.735 --> 01:16:06.817
and the bank is forcing
you to do something,

01:16:07.112 --> 01:16:08.898
the bank is forcing
you to sell japan.

01:16:09.198 --> 01:16:11.405
japan was making
all kinds of money.

01:16:11.700 --> 01:16:13.736
i mean, selling japan
was a terrible loss.

01:16:18.874 --> 01:16:20.364
[steve]
they expanded too much.

01:16:20.667 --> 01:16:23.830
that hurt them whether there
had been a napster or not.

01:16:24.129 --> 01:16:25.619
the fact that there was
a napster later

01:16:25.923 --> 01:16:26.878
sort of was the death blow.

01:16:27.174 --> 01:16:28.880
[phone ringing]

01:16:29.176 --> 01:16:30.962
well, here's russ now.

01:16:31.261 --> 01:16:32.171
i'm being interviewed.

01:16:34.014 --> 01:16:35.424
[russ]bud martin.

01:16:35.724 --> 01:16:38.340
if bud had not gotten sick
and died on me,

01:16:38.644 --> 01:16:40.760
for crying out loud,
and i'd have listened to him,

01:16:41.063 --> 01:16:42.303
i wouldn't have been
in the problems

01:16:42.606 --> 01:16:44.471
that I had later on,
i'll tell ya.

01:16:46.527 --> 01:16:49.234
[rudy]people appreciated
what bud did eventually.

01:16:49.530 --> 01:16:52.317
bud was a cool guy,
and I know when a few drinks,

01:16:52.616 --> 01:16:55.232
the old story about him
swinging on chandeliers

01:16:55.536 --> 01:16:58.494
at the red lion, putting
lampshades on his head

01:16:58.789 --> 01:17:01.576
running around, but they felt
like he was the rock

01:17:01.875 --> 01:17:03.160
of the company also.

01:17:03.460 --> 01:17:05.826
he was the guy
that took care of business.

01:17:06.130 --> 01:17:07.711
[russ]he got older
and sicker is all.

01:17:08.006 --> 01:17:10.839
he had an illness,
which he had for a long time.

01:17:14.805 --> 01:17:18.263
[mike]he had not really told
anybody by the early '9os,

01:17:18.559 --> 01:17:22.302
but he was suffering from
a debilitating illness,

01:17:22.604 --> 01:17:25.971
leukemia, which,
unbeknownst to most of us,

01:17:26.275 --> 01:17:29.767
he had had for...
maybe 15 years.

01:17:30.070 --> 01:17:31.276
he had a good life.

01:17:31.572 --> 01:17:33.608
it was sad at the end
when it ended.

01:17:33.907 --> 01:17:36.148
he didn't have much
at all to speak of.

01:17:38.579 --> 01:17:40.865
[mike]it was only
a couple of years later

01:17:41.165 --> 01:17:42.780
that he passed away.

01:17:47.796 --> 01:17:49.832
[heidi]
anyway, I have a couple things
i want to say about bud.

01:17:50.132 --> 01:17:52.498
i may not get this
out right, excuse me.

01:17:55.262 --> 01:17:57.127
i wasn't going to do this.

01:17:57.431 --> 01:18:00.047
he really taught all of us,
us young kids

01:18:00.350 --> 01:18:01.556
who are now vice presidents

01:18:01.852 --> 01:18:03.262
to take a look

01:18:03.562 --> 01:18:05.974
at what we were
doing with our lives

01:18:06.273 --> 01:18:09.015
as far as
our morality was concerned.

01:18:09.318 --> 01:18:11.684
he was a wonderful
teacher to us.

01:18:11.987 --> 01:18:13.318
he was an incredible sexist pig,

01:18:13.614 --> 01:18:15.696
but at the same time
he was entirely fair.

01:18:15.991 --> 01:18:18.198
so after that, I only have one
thing more to say.

01:18:18.494 --> 01:18:20.030
if I can get this out.

01:18:20.329 --> 01:18:21.990
[sniffles] sorry.

01:18:22.289 --> 01:18:24.871
okay. bud, baby,

01:18:25.167 --> 01:18:26.998
this one's for you.

01:18:27.294 --> 01:18:28.659
[russ]bud martin.

01:18:28.962 --> 01:18:32.170
bud, of all people, was making
things possible to do.

01:18:34.051 --> 01:18:36.417
you know, after all
of those 26 years,

01:18:36.720 --> 01:18:39.382
probably the last
three years were spent

01:18:39.681 --> 01:18:42.798
feeling that the whole idea
of Tower Records

01:18:43.101 --> 01:18:44.966
was not going to be
around much longer.

01:18:45.270 --> 01:18:48.228
at the end, for me,
it was just a matter of when.

01:18:48.524 --> 01:18:49.730
when the banks came in,

01:18:50.025 --> 01:18:51.014
we knew that things
were going to change.

01:18:51.318 --> 01:18:53.354
it was, it was...

01:18:55.322 --> 01:18:56.607
my father...

01:18:59.409 --> 01:19:01.570
when the banks started
putting pressure

01:19:01.870 --> 01:19:04.486
on the company
and insisting that we hire

01:19:04.790 --> 01:19:07.953
a restructuring officer
to run the company,

01:19:08.252 --> 01:19:09.583
my father

01:19:09.878 --> 01:19:11.368
became very upset.

01:19:13.131 --> 01:19:15.838
[russ]
the bank broke me that news.

01:19:16.134 --> 01:19:18.125
and I said, "i don't think
it's a good idea. "

01:19:18.428 --> 01:19:20.089
they said,
"well this is your choice,

01:19:20.389 --> 01:19:21.424
"you either bring
in new management

01:19:21.723 --> 01:19:23.554
or we don't loan you the money."

01:19:23.850 --> 01:19:25.511
so I say, "okay,
we need the money.

01:19:25.811 --> 01:19:28.473
we have to have the money,
or we can't operate at all,

01:19:28.772 --> 01:19:32.356
so okay, we'll try to bring
in new management."

01:19:32.651 --> 01:19:35.108
mike goes down
to hire this woman,

01:19:35.404 --> 01:19:37.395
betsy burton,
he wants to hire her.

01:19:37.698 --> 01:19:40.064
[bob delanoy]these new bodies
were in. I think it was betsy,

01:19:40.367 --> 01:19:41.607
i didn't even know

01:19:41.910 --> 01:19:43.116
what was going on
in the company at the time.

01:19:43.412 --> 01:19:45.403
her idea was to spend all this

01:19:45.706 --> 01:19:49.164
marketing money on branding,
and you're just going,

01:19:49.459 --> 01:19:51.415
"why are you going to spend
this money on branding?

01:19:51.712 --> 01:19:53.077
we're already
established as a brand.

01:19:53.380 --> 01:19:55.336
what you need is retail ads.

01:19:55.632 --> 01:19:57.964
you need ads that
are going to move product.

01:19:58.260 --> 01:20:00.216
you need to move product.
that's the bottom line."

01:20:00.512 --> 01:20:03.424
and then she closed
down pulse magazine.

01:20:03.724 --> 01:20:07.512
[mike]losing pulse, firing
30 or 40 employees,

01:20:07.811 --> 01:20:09.176
was heartbreaking.

01:20:09.479 --> 01:20:13.188
if I ever came close
to wanting to kill somebody,

01:20:13.483 --> 01:20:15.895
with my hands, it was her.

01:20:16.194 --> 01:20:18.230
[mike]we closed
our print shop, I believe,

01:20:18.530 --> 01:20:21.192
and to lose 30 employees.

01:20:21.491 --> 01:20:24.528
we closed our sign shop
and lost 30 employees.

01:20:24.828 --> 01:20:27.615
we had to make cuts every place.
we had to fire people.

01:20:27.914 --> 01:20:30.621
and that is where you just
had the two feelings of,

01:20:30.917 --> 01:20:33.283
"i'm so good, i'm not going
to be gone, I hope."

01:20:33.587 --> 01:20:35.623
the restructuring officers
were coming in and saying,

01:20:35.922 --> 01:20:37.207
" look, you gotta cut
your expenses

01:20:37.507 --> 01:20:38.872
because you don't have
any money."

01:20:39.176 --> 01:20:40.586
in a way, they were
saying the same thing

01:20:40.886 --> 01:20:43.628
that bud was saying
for the last four decades.

01:20:43.930 --> 01:20:46.717
you know, I had
the one side of my mouth

01:20:47.017 --> 01:20:49.053
sit with him
and try to figure out

01:20:49.353 --> 01:20:51.309
growing the company and how
to get out of this mess,

01:20:51.605 --> 01:20:53.345
and the other side of my mouth,

01:20:53.649 --> 01:20:57.233
deal with th ese guys that want
to just tear everything down.

01:20:57.527 --> 01:20:59.142
for me, I was conflicted.

01:20:59.446 --> 01:21:01.812
they don't understand
the product,

01:21:02.115 --> 01:21:05.198
they don't understand the people
that worked for the company,

01:21:05.494 --> 01:21:06.984
they don't understand
the systems,

01:21:07.287 --> 01:21:08.402
they don't understand anything.

01:21:08.705 --> 01:21:11.822
the seeds of failure
are built in to it.

01:21:12.125 --> 01:21:13.410
and it can't last.

01:21:13.710 --> 01:21:17.202
he basically fought
the restructuring officers--

01:21:17.506 --> 01:21:18.996
there were numerous
of them that came in.

01:21:19.299 --> 01:21:23.087
and I remember so vividly
going to the first meeting.

01:21:23.387 --> 01:21:26.254
i talked to them, and I say,
"well now, i'm on the board,

01:21:26.556 --> 01:21:28.387
"and i've still got
the officially

01:21:28.684 --> 01:21:30.265
"the chairman of the company.

01:21:30.560 --> 01:21:33.302
i mean, that's a chairman
without portfolio,"

01:21:33.605 --> 01:21:35.095
i said,
"what do you want me to do?

01:21:35.399 --> 01:21:36.855
"who's going to be
the visionary?

01:21:37.150 --> 01:21:39.391
"who's going to think about
what we should be doing

01:21:39.695 --> 01:21:41.105
in this industry
in the future?"

01:21:41.405 --> 01:21:44.147
and this idiot woman
says to me,

01:21:44.449 --> 01:21:45.689
"we don't need a visionary."

01:21:47.285 --> 01:21:49.276
i can't control
anything anymore.

01:21:49.579 --> 01:21:51.991
so what was I to do?
just shake my head and walk off.

01:21:52.290 --> 01:21:53.450
betsy had interviewed the group,

01:21:53.750 --> 01:21:57.038
and if I remember,
most of us individually

01:21:57.337 --> 01:22:00.420
who were in senior management,
so we knew what was going on.

01:22:00.716 --> 01:22:05.881
and mike solomon was
promoted to president,

01:22:06.179 --> 01:22:10.297
and he had to do what
th ese bank guys wanted to do,

01:22:10.600 --> 01:22:12.431
and so everything just
kind of had stopped.

01:22:12.728 --> 01:22:14.264
somebody who was an outsider

01:22:14.563 --> 01:22:16.645
was taking it away from us.

01:22:16.940 --> 01:22:19.397
i was caught
in the middle, really.

01:22:19.693 --> 01:22:21.183
we needed to be
profitable, basically,

01:22:21.486 --> 01:22:24.353
and we needed to pay our debt.
but to do that,

01:22:24.656 --> 01:22:27.819
we basically had to cut
the heart out of the company.

01:22:28.118 --> 01:22:32.737
[stan]in 2004, they got rid
of me and dee

01:22:33.039 --> 01:22:34.279
and mark viducich,

01:22:34.583 --> 01:22:36.323
i guess they decided,
i think then,

01:22:36.626 --> 01:22:37.365
to liquidate the company.

01:22:37.669 --> 01:22:38.784
they didn't say it,

01:22:39.087 --> 01:22:41.954
and it took 'em
a few years to do it,

01:22:42.257 --> 01:22:43.713
but they were no longer

01:22:44.009 --> 01:22:45.624
interested in trying
to either grow the company

01:22:45.927 --> 01:22:48.134
or save the company,
in my opinion.

01:22:48.430 --> 01:22:51.513
they told us,
and instructed us

01:22:51.808 --> 01:22:55.596
what we had to do
to cut costs, save money,

01:22:55.896 --> 01:22:59.354
increase profits if we could,
or at least decrease losses,

01:22:59.649 --> 01:23:00.980
so if we can fire someone making

01:23:01.276 --> 01:23:04.234
200,000, we can hire
someone making 100,000.

01:23:04.529 --> 01:23:05.644
i was in mike solomon's office

01:23:05.947 --> 01:23:10.190
with he and a lady
we call betty boop,

01:23:10.494 --> 01:23:11.825
and you know why you're there.

01:23:12.120 --> 01:23:13.951
it's not a secret,
i told him and betty,

01:23:14.247 --> 01:23:16.329
"you guys are the ones
that shouldn't be here.

01:23:16.625 --> 01:23:18.707
you guys are the people
that should be fired, not me."

01:23:19.002 --> 01:23:21.618
firing people that you
had hired 30 years ago.

01:23:21.922 --> 01:23:25.039
people that you know,
were started as clerks

01:23:25.342 --> 01:23:29.130
that were now regional managers
or vps or whatever.

01:23:29.429 --> 01:23:32.216
it's just, you know, awful.

01:23:32.516 --> 01:23:34.256
stanley and I were
up at lake tahoe.

01:23:34.559 --> 01:23:38.393
we're having a drink after
doing some gambling at the bar,

01:23:38.688 --> 01:23:42.806
and out of the blue,
he says, "oh bob, by the way,

01:23:43.109 --> 01:23:44.519
we're restructuring
the company."

01:23:44.820 --> 01:23:46.151
"we need to structure
the company

01:23:46.446 --> 01:23:48.357
because of growth or whatever,"

01:23:48.657 --> 01:23:51.239
and I was just like, stunned.

01:23:51.535 --> 01:23:54.993
because, I mean,
this little private setting.

01:23:55.288 --> 01:23:58.405
so, I mean,
i was hammering down
some scotches at that point.

01:23:58.708 --> 01:24:00.323
the day heidi fired me,
you know,

01:24:00.627 --> 01:24:02.333
she called me in one day
and she says,

01:24:02.629 --> 01:24:04.244
"rudy, this is hard
for me to say,

01:24:04.548 --> 01:24:07.836
but I want a divorce."

01:24:08.134 --> 01:24:10.750
it was really hard,
and I knew it was hard for her

01:24:11.054 --> 01:24:14.262
as it was for me,
you know, and so,

01:24:14.558 --> 01:24:16.389
i went to russ, he said,
"now what the fuck

01:24:16.685 --> 01:24:18.346
are we going to do with you?"
like that.

01:24:18.645 --> 01:24:20.727
he never fired anybody
in his life.

01:24:21.022 --> 01:24:23.354
let alone his whole executive
committee for christ sakes.

01:24:23.650 --> 01:24:26.266
Â— it's not who he was.
- he took me out for lunch.

01:24:26.570 --> 01:24:27.810
actually called me and he said,
"want to go to lunch?"

01:24:28.113 --> 01:24:30.946
and I thought,
"this is not boding well.

01:24:31.241 --> 01:24:32.651
"russ doesn't call you
and ask you to lunch.

01:24:32.951 --> 01:24:34.737
this is not..." you know.
and he was in tears.

01:24:35.036 --> 01:24:37.948
i mean, it was as hard
for him as it was for me.

01:24:38.248 --> 01:24:39.863
it was probably harder,
i felt worse for him.

01:24:40.166 --> 01:24:43.283
russ and I are cousins,
and mike solomon,

01:24:43.587 --> 01:24:47.500
who was also the ceo
at one time, and I are cousins,

01:24:47.799 --> 01:24:51.132
and to see family members
just thrown aside too

01:24:51.428 --> 01:24:56.092
was harder than just
losing a 30-year career.

01:24:56.391 --> 01:24:59.804
and at the end of 30 years,
i got a watch.

01:25:00.103 --> 01:25:03.015
just shortly after
i left the company.

01:25:03.315 --> 01:25:05.306
in fact, i'm wearing it
right now, today.

01:25:07.235 --> 01:25:08.520
and it says,

01:25:08.820 --> 01:25:11.653
" bob, thank you, we love
you, Tower Records."

01:25:16.745 --> 01:25:18.576
and uh, it was mutual.

01:25:24.669 --> 01:25:27.285
[ken]! wish probably
that I could say there was more

01:25:27.589 --> 01:25:30.126
survivor's guilt, but, um,

01:25:31.635 --> 01:25:34.251
there was a lot of relief too.

01:25:34.554 --> 01:25:38.263
[interviewer]and then
as more layoffs happened...?

01:25:39.476 --> 01:25:40.807
no?

01:25:48.485 --> 01:25:51.101
[Mike Solomon] Cutting
the essential parts of Tower

01:25:51.404 --> 01:25:54.567
that made it so successful
was heart wrenching.

01:25:54.866 --> 01:25:56.072
that was the heart
of the company.

01:25:56.368 --> 01:25:57.904
i mean, the company
wasn't going to run

01:25:58.203 --> 01:26:00.694
without this team.

01:26:00.997 --> 01:26:02.988
and sure enough it didn't.

01:26:03.291 --> 01:26:05.373
[male reporter 1]tonight,
the founder of Tower Records

01:26:05.669 --> 01:26:07.830
is closing his last
retail record store.

01:26:08.129 --> 01:26:10.040
[female reporter]it's the end
of the line for an icon

01:26:10.340 --> 01:26:11.546
that put sacramento on the map.

01:26:11.841 --> 01:26:13.206
[male reporter 2]
one of several chains

01:26:13.510 --> 01:26:15.296
closing its doors nationwide.

01:26:15.595 --> 01:26:17.551
[melancholy piano music playing]

01:26:22.602 --> 01:26:24.888
[russ]! was in new york
at fourth and broadway,

01:26:25.188 --> 01:26:27.474
and we had an apartment
in the same building

01:26:27.774 --> 01:26:31.312
and I was staying there,
looking at the store

01:26:31.611 --> 01:26:33.147
when it closed that night.

01:26:33.446 --> 01:26:35.562
stood across the street
and watched, yeah.

01:26:37.325 --> 01:26:39.782
what are you going to do?
it's over.

01:26:40.078 --> 01:26:41.614
they all shut down at once,
and a bunch of people

01:26:41.913 --> 01:26:44.325
lost their job at the end.

01:26:44.624 --> 01:26:46.785
it was one of the greatest
tragedies of my life,

01:26:47.085 --> 01:26:48.450
to be honest with you,
when it closed down.

01:26:48.753 --> 01:26:50.960
it really, really upset me.

01:26:51.256 --> 01:26:53.747
and I missed it,
i missed that routine of going

01:26:54.050 --> 01:26:56.962
to buy my records
or my cds or whatever.

01:26:57.262 --> 01:26:59.423
[ken]it really was
this organization,

01:26:59.723 --> 01:27:03.557
this camaraderie, this group
that coalesced around russ

01:27:03.852 --> 01:27:05.808
and was able to feed off

01:27:06.104 --> 01:27:08.811
and build on russ' vision.

01:27:14.029 --> 01:27:17.692
in the early 70's,
i took a job at Tower Broadway

01:27:17.991 --> 01:27:19.902
here in sacramento,
at 16th and broadway,

01:27:20.201 --> 01:27:21.691
and in 1992,

01:27:21.995 --> 01:27:25.783
i actually ended up here
at watt avenue as the manager.

01:27:26.082 --> 01:27:27.572
we have a marquee out
on the front of our store

01:27:27.876 --> 01:27:30.037
that we just advertise
what's going on

01:27:30.336 --> 01:27:31.872
in the store
and what's happening.

01:27:32.172 --> 01:27:33.582
when we got the word

01:27:33.882 --> 01:27:35.964
that the liquidators
had won the auction

01:27:36.259 --> 01:27:38.545
and it was imminent that
it was going to be the end,

01:27:38.845 --> 01:27:40.801
we wanted to put something
up on the marquee.

01:27:41.097 --> 01:27:43.679
one of my employees,
dale, came up with:

01:27:43.975 --> 01:27:47.763
all things must pass.
thanks, sacramento.

01:27:48.063 --> 01:27:51.271
i went home, and the next
day I came in to work,

01:27:51.566 --> 01:27:52.851
they had taken a huge banner

01:27:53.151 --> 01:27:55.267
that was like 100-feet
long it seemed like,

01:27:55.570 --> 01:27:57.185
that said basically going
out of business.

01:27:57.489 --> 01:27:59.195
and they put
that banner up across

01:27:59.491 --> 01:28:01.402
the whole top of the exterior
of the building,

01:28:01.701 --> 01:28:04.033
covered up our sign that said
"all things must pass",

01:28:04.329 --> 01:28:05.865
and you know,
it was pretty deflating.

01:28:06.164 --> 01:28:08.496
it was like, you know reality
slaps you right in the face.

01:28:08.792 --> 01:28:10.453
when they were finally gone,
they took down the sign,

01:28:10.752 --> 01:28:13.334
and exposed our message
one more time.

01:28:18.968 --> 01:28:20.174
it's really sad.

01:28:21.721 --> 01:28:23.677
the skeleton is still here.

01:28:23.973 --> 01:28:28.182
and the parts are still here,
even though they're not working.

01:28:32.357 --> 01:28:34.689
and it was filled with records.

01:28:34.984 --> 01:28:36.474
and the music was playing.

01:28:36.778 --> 01:28:39.690
and the people were running
around and shopping.

01:28:39.989 --> 01:28:42.822
but then again,
that's the past.

01:28:44.786 --> 01:28:47.323
there's no way
you can change that.

01:28:47.622 --> 01:28:49.738
let's think about what
to do in the future.

